[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 1/5 answer="Let's break it down step-by-step:\n\n1. Melanie started with \\( V \\) vacuum cleaners.\n2. She sold a third at the green house, so she kept \\( \\frac{V}{3} \\).\n   - Then she sold 2 more at the red house, so she had \\( \\frac{V}{3} + 2 \\).\n   - She sold half of what remained at the orange house, so she had \\( 2(\\frac{V}{3} + 2) \\) left.\n3. According to the problem, she has 5 vacuum cleaners left, so we can set up the equation:\n\\[ 2(\\frac{V}{3} + 2) = 5 \\]\n4. Solving for \\( V \\):\n\\[ \\frac{V}{3} + 2 = \\frac{5}{2} \\]\n\\[ \\frac{V}{3} = \\frac{5}{2} - 2 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{V}{3} = \\frac{5}{2} - \\frac{4}{2} \\]\n\\[ \\frac{V}{3} = \\frac{1}{2} \\]\n\\[ V = \\frac{3}{2} \\]\n\nSo, Melanie started with \\( \\frac{3}{2} \\) vacuum cleaners, which is 1.5 vacuum cleaners. Since the number of vacuum cleaners must be whole numbers, let's round to the nearest whole number. Therefore, Melanie started with 2 vacuum cleaners."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 2/5 answer="Let's break down Melanie's sales:\n\n1. At the green house, she sold a third of her vacuum cleaners:\n   \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times 5 = \\frac{5}{3} \\approx 1.67 \\) (approximately)\n   So, she had 1.67 + 1 = 2.67 vacuums remaining.\n   \n2. At the red house, she sold 2 more than a third of what she had from the previous sale:\n   \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times 2.67 = 0.89 \\approx 1.00 \\) (approximately)\n   So, she had 2.67 - 1 = 1.67 remaining.\n   \n3. At the orange house, she sold half of what was left at the previous sale:\n   \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\times 1.67 = 0.83 \\approx 0.84 \\) (approximately)\n   So, she had 1.67 - 0.83 = 0.84 remaining.\n   \nFinally, since she started with 5 vacuum cleaners and 0.84 were left:\n   \\( 5 - 0.84 = 4.16 \\)\n\nSo, Melanie started with approximately 4.16 vacuum cleaners."
