[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 4/5 answer="To find out how many vacuum cleaners Melanie started with, let's break down the problem step by step:\n\n1. Melanie sold a third of her vacuum cleaners at the green house, which means she had:\n   1 (total) - 1/3 (from the green house) = 2/3 (from the green house)\n\n2. At the red house, she sold 2 more than what she had from the green house, so she sold:\n   2/3 (she already had from the green house) + 2 = 5/3 (from the red house)\n\n3. Now, we have 5 vacuum cleaners remaining. Since we know 5/3 came from the red house, it means:\n   5/3 (remaining) = 5/3\n\n4. To find the total number of vacuum cleaners she initially had:\n   We'll set up an equation where x represents the initial number of vacuum cleaners (we assume she originally had x):\n\n   x - (5/3) = 5\n\n5. Solving for x:\n   x = 5 + 5/3\n   x = 15/3 + 5/3\n   x = 20/3\n\nTherefore, Melanie started with 20/3 (or approximately 6.67) vacuum cleaners."
