ac{V - \\left(\\frac{4V}{3} + 2\\right)}{2} = 5 \\]\n\n4. Multiply both sides by 2 to clear the fraction:\n   \\[ V - \\': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 start id=gsm8k_test_51
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 1/5 answer='First, we calculate the time Tom spends traveling from 1 to 4 PM. This takes \\(4 - 1 = 3\\) hours. \n\nNext, we calculate the time he spends traveling back. Since his speed on the return trip is 6 mph, the time required would be \\( \\frac{4}{6} = \\frac{2}{3} \\) hours.\n\nTo find out how long it takes him to return, we add both parts together:\n\n\\[ 3 + \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{9}{3} + \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{11}{3} \\]\n\nConverting \\(\\frac{11}{3}\\) to a decimal gives us approximately 3.67 hours.\n\nTherefore, it takes Tom approximately 3.67 hours to complete his round trip.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 2/5 answer="To calculate how long it takes Tom to return, we first need to determine when he starts traveling again. Since he was sailing from 1 to 4 PM and traveled at 10 mph for some period during that time, let's assume he started at 1 PM. He would have been traveling for 4 hours (from 1 PM to 4 PM) or possibly shorter if he started earlier than 1 PM.\n\nNow, since his speed is 10 mph and he stopped halfway through the trip:\n\nHe spends 2 hours on the trip before returning. \n\nAt 6 mph, this would take:\n\\[ \\frac{2 \\text{ hours}}{6 \\text{ mph}} = \\frac{1}{3} \\text{ hour} \\]\n\nSince there are 60 minutes in an hour, we convert hours to minutes:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\text{ hour} \\times 60 \\text{ minutes/hour} = 20 \\text{ minutes} \\]\n\nSo, it takes him **20 minutes** to return."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/5 answer='78'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's calculate how far Tom sails between 1 PM and 2 PM:\nDistance = Speed × Time\nTom sails at 10 mph for 1 hour, so he covers 10 × 1 = 10 miles.\n\nNow, we know he has to cover 4 - 2 = 2 hours (from 2 PM to 4 PM) to return home. Since he travels back at a speed of 6 mph, we can calculate the distance he will cover on his return trip like this:\n\nDistance = Speed × Time\nDistance = 6 mph × 2 hours = 12 miles\n\nSo, the total distance Tom travels between 1 PM and 4 PM is 10 + 12 = 22 miles.\n\nTo find out how long it takes him to complete the round trip, we divide the total distance by his speed:\n\nTime = Distance / Speed\nTime = 22 miles / 10 mph = 2.2 hours.\n\nTherefore, the time it takes Tom to get back to where he started is 2.2 hours."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 5/5 answer="First, let's calculate how long it takes Tom to sail from 1 to 4 PM:\n\nTom sails at 10 mph for 3 hours (from 1 to 4 PM).\n\nSo, the time taken to sail is:\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Speed}} = \\frac{3 \\text{ hours}}{10 \\text{ mph}} = 0.3 \\text{ hours} \\]\n\nNext, we calculate how long it takes him to return:\n\nHe travels at 6 mph for 2 hours (since he already sailed for 3 hours).\n\nSo, the time taken to return is:\n\\[ \\text{Time} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Speed}} = \\frac{2 \\text{ hours}}{6 \\text{ mph}} = \\frac{1}{3} \\text{ hours} \\]\n\nNow, to find out the total time spent, we add both parts together:\n\\[ \\text{Total Time} = 0.3 \\text{ hours} + \\frac{1}{3} \\text{ hours} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Time} = 0.9 \\text{ hours} + 0.333\\ldots \\text{ hours} \\approx 1.233 \\text{ hours} \\]\n\nTo convert hours into minutes, we multiply by 60 (since there are 60 minutes in an hour):\n\\[ \\text{Total Time (minutes)} = 1.233 \\times 60 \\approx 74.98 \\text{ minutes} \\]\n\nTherefore, it would take Tom approximately 74.98 minutes (or about 1 hour and 40 minutes) to complete his journey back from 1 to 4 PM."
