[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 4/100 path 2/5 answer="To calculate how much Janet paid, we need to add up all the costs mentioned:\n\n1. Brooch material cost: $500\n2. Jeweler's construction cost: $800\n3. Insurance cost (10%) of the total amount: 10/100 * ($500 + $800) = $110\n\nNow let's add these amounts together:\n$500 (material) + $800 (jeweler) + $110 (insurance) = $1410\n\nTherefore, Janet paid $1410 for the brooch."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 4/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 4/100 path 3/5 answer='First, we calculate the cost of the brooch itself, which includes the material cost ($500) plus the additional $800 needed to construct it (since the brooch is made from materials). \nCost of material: $500\nCost of construction: $800\nTotal cost before insurance: $500 + $800 = $1300\n\nNext, we calculate the amount paid for the insurance, which is 10% of the total cost before insurance.\nInsurance cost: 10% * $1300 = $130\n\nFinally, we subtract the insurance cost from the total cost before insurance to find out how much Janet paid:\nFinal payment: $1300 - $130 = $1170\n\nSo, Janet paid $1170.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 4/100 path 4/5 start
