[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 2/5 answer="To find out how many copies Harald sold, we can set up an equation based on the information given. Let's denote the number of copies Harald sold as \\( H \\). According to the problem:\n\n\\[ 10H + 88000 = 88000 \\]\n\nWe know that \\( 10H \\) represents the number of copies sold by Marilyn, who sold 10 times as many as Harald. Rearranging this equation to solve for \\( H \\), we get:\n\n\\[ 10H = 88000 - 88000 \\]\n\\[ 10H = 0 \\]\n\nSo,\n\n\\[ H = 0 \\]\n\nTherefore, Harald sold 0 copies."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 3/5 answer='8000'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 4/5 answer="To find out how many copies Harald sold, let's denote the number of copies Harald sold as H. According to the information given:\n\n10 (times) = Marilyn's sales\n\nSo, if Marilyn sold 10 times as many copies as Harald, we can set up the equation:\n\nH = 10H\n\nSince they sold 88,000 copies together, we have:\n\nH + 10H = 88,000\n\nCombining like terms gives us:\n\n11H = 88,000\n\nDividing both sides by 11:\n\nH = 88,000 / 11\n\nH = 8,000\n\nTherefore, Harald sold 8,000 copies."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 6/100 path 5/5 answer="To find out how many copies Harald sold, we can set up a proportion based on the information given:\n\nMarilyn's sales (M) : Harald's sales (H) = 10 : 1\n\nGiven that Marilyn sold 88,000 copies:\n\n10/1 = 88,000/H\n\nCross-multiplying gives us:\n\n10H = 88,000\n\nDividing both sides by 10:\n\nH = 88,000 / 10\n\nH = 8,800\n\nSo, Harald sold 8,800 copies."
