[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 start id=gsm8k_test_93
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 1/5 answer='To determine how fast Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles with his improved diet, we first calculate his original running time. Since he used to take 2 seconds less than Lee, Lee took 38 + 2 = 40 seconds. This means Gerald now takes 40 + 2 = 42 seconds to finish the race. With a 10% improvement in speed, Gerald’s current running time becomes 42 * (1 + 0.1) = 42 * 1.1 = 46.2 seconds.\n\nSo, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles in 46.2 seconds.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 2/5 answer="Lee ran the 400-meter hurdles in 38 seconds using the information that he could run it two seconds quicker than Gerald. This means Gerald's time was 38 + 2 = <<38+2=40>>40 seconds.\nGerald's initial improvement from running at double Lee's rate was 10% of 40 seconds, which is 0.10 * 40 = <<0.10*40=4>>4 seconds.\nWith this improvement, Gerald increased his time by 4 seconds, bringing it to 40 + 4 = <<40+4=44>>44 seconds.\nTherefore, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles in 44 seconds."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 3/5 answer="To find out how fast Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles with his improved diet, we first need to determine Lee's running time in the original scenario.\n\nLee can run the 400-meter hurdles in 38 seconds.\n\nAccording to the information given:\n- Lee used to be able to run it 2 seconds faster than Gerald.\n- Lee ran it in 38 seconds originally.\nSo, Gerald's original running time was \\(38 + 2\\) seconds.\n\nNow, let's calculate Gerald's original running time:\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original running time} = 38 + 2 = 40 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nNext, we'll consider the changes due to Gerald's diet. His diet allowed him to improve his speed by 10%.\n\nLet's denote Gerald's original speed as \\(v\\).\n\nWith his increased speed, his new speed will be \\(v + 10\\%\\).\n\nWe also know that Gerald's original speed \\(v\\) was such that he could have completed the 400 meters in 40 seconds.\n\nIn Gerald's new condition, his new speed will be calculated as:\n\\[ v + 0.1v = 1.1v \\]\n\nSince the new speed allows Gerald to complete the 400 meters in 40 seconds, we can write:\n\\[ 1.1v = 40 \\]\n\nSolving for \\(v\\):\n\\[ v = \\frac{40}{1.1} \\]\n\\[ v = \\frac{40}{1.1} \\approx 36.36 \\]\n\nTherefore, Gerald's original speed was approximately **36.36** seconds per meter (or approximately **36.4 seconds per meter** if considering rounding).\n\nFinally, using the formula for Gerald's new speed:\n\\["
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's determine Lee's original time to run the 400-meter hurdles:\n\nLee was able to run it two seconds faster than Gerald. Given that Lee took 38 seconds to do so, we subtract 2 from that time to find out Gerald's time:\n\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's time} = 38\\, \\text{seconds} - 2\\, \\text{seconds} = 36\\, \\text{seconds} \\]\n\nNow, we know that Gerald's running time increased by 10% due to his improved diet. To find out how long his time became after the increase, we calculate 10% of 36 seconds:\n\n\\[ \\text{Increased time} = 0.10 \\times 36\\, \\text{seconds} = 3.6\\, \\text{seconds} \\]\n\nFinally, to find out Gerald's new time after the diet change, we add that increase to his original time:\n\n\\[ \\text{New time} = 36\\, \\text{seconds} + 3.6\\, \\text{seconds} = 39.6\\, \\text{seconds} \\]\n\nTherefore, Gerald can now run the 400-meter hurdles at a speed of 39.6 seconds."
