ted that Jamal's phone can hold 50 times the number of birds in her photograph, which was 1800 photographs. So:\n\nNumber of photographs in Brittany's phone = 50 × Number of birds in Jamal's photograph\nNumber of photographs in Brittany's phone = 50 × 1800\nNumber of photographs in Brittany's phone = 90,000\n\nTo find out how many ducks can be seen in the photograph, we divide the total number of photographs in the phone by the number of photographs each duck can hold. Each duck can hold 1 photograph:\n\nNumber of ducks = Total number of photographs ÷ Number of photographs per duck\nNumber of ducks = 90,000 ÷ 1\nNumber of ducks = 90,000\n\nSo, there would be 90,000 ducks in Jamal's photograph of ducks at the zoo if the conditions were met.": 1, "First, we find out how many photographs Jamal’s phone can hold: 1800 photos.\nIt holds 6 times more than Brittany's phone, so Brittany's phone can hold: 1800 ÷ 6 = <<1800/6=300>>300 photos.\nBrittany's phone could also hold 50 times more than the number of birds in Jamal's photo, meaning there are 50 × 1800 = <<50*1800=90000>>90,000 birds in her photo.\nSo, the number of ducks she was able to see is 90,000 (birds) divided by 2 (for each duck): 90,000 / 2 = <<90000/2=45,000>>45,000 ducks.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 start id=gsm8k_test_135
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 1/5 answer="First, let's calculate the number of video games Brian's friend Bobby has based on the information given:\n\nBrian has 20 video games, so if he had lost some games first, we don't know the exact count yet. But since we're looking at Bobby's total, we can ignore any games lost by Brian and focus only on what he has now.\n\nBobby has \\( 5 \\) fewer than \\( 3 \\times\\) Brian's original amount:\n\\[ 3 \\times 20 - 5 = 60 - 5 = 55 \\]\n\nSo, Bobby has 55 video games in total. Since we don't have any additional information about how many games Brian or his friend Bobby have lost, we'll assume they haven't lost any more games (as they didn't lose anything initially).\n\nTo find out how many video games Bobby has left:\n\n\\[ 55 - 5 = 50 \\]\n\nThus, Bobby has 50 video games remaining."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 2/5 answer='First, we determine the initial number of video games Bobby has:\n- Brian has 20 video games.\n- He lost 5 before the comparison, so his remaining video games are \\(20 - 5 = 15\\).\n\nNext, we calculate what Bobby has based on the given relationship:\n- Bobby has 5 fewer than 3 times the number of video games Brian originally had.\n- Brian originally had \\(3 \\times 20 = 60\\) video games.\n- According to the problem, Bobby has \\(60 - 5 = 55\\) video games.\n\nThus, Bobby has 55 video games.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 3/5 answer='First, we calculate how many video games Brian actually has. He had 20 video games initially minus the 5 he lost, so he now has 20 - 5 = 15 video games. Now we can find out how many video games Bobby has by calculating 5 times the number of video games Brian originally had (which is 3 times the number Brian has), then subtracting the 5 games he lost before the comparison.\n\nSo, Bobby has 3 * 15 - 5 = 45 + 5 = <<3*15-5=45+5=50>>50 video games.\n\nBobby has 50 video games.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 4/5 answer="To determine how many video games Bobby has, we first need to find out how many video games Brian originally had. Since Brian originally had 20 video games, he lost 5 right before the comparison was made, so his original number of video games is \\(20 + 5 = 25\\). \n\nNow, we know that Bobby has 5 fewer than 3 times the number of video games that Brian has. This can be calculated as follows:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = (3 \\times \\text{Brian's original number}) - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = (3 \\times 25) - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = 75 - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = 70 \\]\n\nTherefore, Bobby has 70 video games."
