han 3 times the number of video games Brian originally had.\n- Brian originally had \\(3 \\times 20 = 60\\) video games.\n- According to the problem, Bobby has \\(60 - 5 = 55\\) video games.\n\nThus, Bobby has 55 video games.': 1, 'First, we calculate how many video games Brian actually has. He had 20 video games initially minus the 5 he lost, so he now has 20 - 5 = 15 video games. Now we can find out how many video games Bobby has by calculating 5 times the number of video games Brian originally had (which is 3 times the number Brian has), then subtracting the 5 games he lost before the comparison.\n\nSo, Bobby has 3 * 15 - 5 = 45 + 5 = <<3*15-5=45+5=50>>50 video games.\n\nBobby has 50 video games.': 1, "To determine how many video games Bobby has, we first need to find out how many video games Brian originally had. Since Brian originally had 20 video games, he lost 5 right before the comparison was made, so his original number of video games is \\(20 + 5 = 25\\). \n\nNow, we know that Bobby has 5 fewer than 3 times the number of video games that Brian has. This can be calculated as follows:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = (3 \\times \\text{Brian's original number}) - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = (3 \\times 25) - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = 75 - 5 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of video games Bobby has} = 70 \\]\n\nTherefore, Bobby has 70 video games.": 1, '55': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 start id=gsm8k_test_142
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 1/5 answer="First, we need to determine how much money Jordan saves on his video game sessions:\n- He spends 2 hours playing each day.\n- He earns $10 per hour.\nSo, the amount saved per session is \\(2 \\times 10 = \\$20\\).\n\nNext, let's calculate the total earnings from his video game sessions over the course of a week (assuming 7 days):\n\\[2 \\text{ hours/day} \\times 20 \\text{ dollars/hour} \\times 7 \\text{ days} = \\$280.\\]\n\nFinally, to find out how much money he would have earned if he had worked all his free time:\n\\[10 \\text{ dollars/hour} \\times 7 \\text{ days} = \\$70.\\]\nTherefore, if Jordan had played video games instead of working, he would have earned $70 in one week."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 2/5 answer='140'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 3/5 answer='First, we calculate how much Jordan spends on playing video games each day:\n\\[ \\text{Daily Video Game Time} = 2 \\, \\text{hours/day} \\]\nThen, we multiply this daily amount by 7 days to get the weekly total:\n\\[ \\text{Weekly Video Game Time} = \\text{Daily Video Game Time} \\times 7 \\]\nTo find out how much he would earn in one week from his gaming session, we use the given hourly rate:\n\\[ \\text{Weekly Earnings} = (\\text{Daily Video Game Time}) \\times (\\text{Hourly Rate}) \\]\nSubstituting in the numbers, we get:\n\\[ \\text{Weekly Earnings} = (2 \\, \\text{hours/day}) \\times (7 \\, \\text{days/week}) \\]\n\\[ \\text{Weekly Earnings} = 14 \\, \\text{dollars/week} \\]\nSo, Jordan would earn $14 in one week if he spent all his video game time working.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 4/5 answer="To calculate how much money Jordan would earn in one week, we'll first determine how much he spends on playing video games and work.\n\nJordan spends 2 hours playing video games each day. Since there are 7 days in a week, he spends:\n2 hours/day × 7 days/week = 14 hours/week\n\nNow, we can calculate his earnings from playing video games:\nEarnings from video games = Hours played/week × Hourly wage\nEarnings from video games = 14 hours/week ÷ 2 hours/hour\nEarnings from video games = $7/week\n\nThen, we multiply the earnings from video games by his hourly rate (which is 10 dollars per hour):\nWeekly earnings from working = Earnings from video games × Hourly wage\nWeekly earnings from working = $7/week × $10/hour\nWeekly earnings from working = $70/week\n\nSo, Jordan would earn $70 in one week if he worked all of his video game time."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 10/100 path 5/5 answer='To calculate how much money Jordan would earn in one week, we first determine how many hours he spends on video games each day and then multiply that by the number of days in a week (assuming 7). \n\nJordan works 2 hours daily playing video games, so in one week (which has 7 days), he would work:\n\n2 hours/day * 7 days/week = 14 hours/week\n\nNow, we calculate his earnings from his jobs. Each hour he earns $10, so in one week (14 hours):\n\n14 hours/week * $10/hour = $140/week\n\nTherefore, Jordan would earn $140 in one week if he spent all his video game time working instead.'
