[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 11/100 path 1/5 answer='First, we calculate the number of legos in each box:\n1. One box with 500 pieces\n2. One box with 3 times more pieces than the first box, so \\(500 \\times 3 = 1500\\) pieces\n3. One box with \\(1/4\\) the number of pieces as the second box, so \\(1500 / 4 = 375\\) pieces\n\nAdding these together gives the total number of legos:\n\\(500 + 1500 + 375 = 2375\\) legos\n\nTherefore, Johnny picks up 2375 legos if he picks them all up.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 11/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 11/100 path 2/5 answer='First, we determine the number of Lego sets Johnny picked up:\n- One set had 500 pieces.\n- The second set had 3 times more pieces than the first, so \\( 3 \\times 500 = 1500 \\) pieces.\n- The third set had \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\) the number of pieces as the second set, so \\( \\frac{1500}{4} = 375 \\) pieces.\n\nNext, we sum the total number of Lego pieces:\n\\[ 500 + 1500 + 375 = 2375 \\]\n\nTherefore, Johnny picks up 2375 Lego pieces.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 11/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 11/100 path 3/5 answer='First, we calculate the number of Lego sets Johnny picked up:\n- The first Lego set has 500 pieces.\n- The second Lego set has 3 times more pieces than the first one, so \\(500 \\times 3 = 1500\\) pieces.\n- The third Lego set has \\(\\frac{1}{4}\\) the number of pieces as the second one, so \\(\\frac{1500}{4} = 375\\) pieces.\n\nNow, we sum these numbers:\n\\(500 + 1500 + 375 = 2375\\)\n\nJohnny picks up 2375 Lego pieces.'
