[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 2/5 answer="First, let's find out how many dolls the doll costs:\nThe doll costs as much as 3 action figures, so it costs 3 action figures × $5/doll = $15.\n\nNow we know the total value of the toys before considering the dolls:\n- Red cars: 5 red cars × $4/car = $20\n- Action figures: 3 action figures × $5/action figure = $15\n\nAdding these together gives us the total value of the toys:\n$20 (red cars) + $15 (action figures) + $15 (doll) = $50\n\nTherefore, all the toys together have a total value of $50."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 3/5 answer="To find out how much each toy is worth, let's first determine the total cost of the dolls:\nEach doll costs as much as 3 action figures, so 1 doll would cost 3 action figures (since 1 doll is equal to 3 action figures). Since we have a total of 3 action figures, each doll costs:\n3 action figures / 3 = $1\n\nNow, let's calculate the cost of the red cars:\nThere are 5 red cars, and they cost $4 each, so the total cost for the red cars is:\n5 red cars * $4/red car = $20\n\nNext, let's sum up the total cost of all the toys:\nDoll cost: $1\nRed cars cost: $20\nAction figures cost: $5 (as given)\n\nSo far, we've added up:\n$1 + $20 + $5 = $26\n\nAdding the doll cost:\n$26 + $4 = $30\n\nTherefore, all the toys together are worth $30."
