[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 start id=gsm8k_test_189
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 1/5 answer="To determine how much each friend paid, we first calculate the total cost of the tickets. Given that three tickets cost $20.25, we divide the total ticket cost by 3:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Cost of one ticket} = \\frac{\\$20.25}{3} = \\$\\frac{2025}{3}\n\\]\n\nNext, since the friends bought 2 rides at $33 each, we find the total cost of these rides:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total cost of rides} = 2 \\times \\$33 = \\$66\n\\]\n\nAdding up the cost of the tickets and the rides gives us the overall amount spent:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total spent} = \\text{Ticket cost} + \\text{Ride cost} = \\$\\frac{2025}{3} + \\$66\n\\]\n\nNow, let's sum up all the costs to find the total amount spent:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total amount spent} = \\$\\frac{2025}{3} + \\$66 = \\$675 + \\$66 = \\$741\n\\]\n\nFinally, to distribute the total amount evenly among the three friends, we divide the total amount by 3:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Amount per friend} = \\frac{\\text{Total amount spent}}{3} = \\frac{\\$741}{3} = \\$247\n\\]\n\nSo, each of the three friends would have to pay $247."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 2/5 answer="Let's break it down:\n\n1. The total amount spent on tickets is $20.25, and they bought 3 tickets.\n   So, each friend would have paid $20.25 ÷ 3 = $6.75 for the tickets.\n\n2. They spent $4.50 less on food than on the tickets.\n   So, the cost of food for one ticket is $20.25 - $4.50 = $15.75\n\n3. Each friend also spends $33 for each ride.\n   Since there are 2 rides, they spend $33 × 2 = $66 on rides.\n\n4. Now we can calculate the total amount spent:\n   Total = Cost of tickets + Cost of food + Cost of rides\n          = $6.75 + $15.75 + $66\n\n5. Let's do the math:\n   Total = $98 (rounded)\n\n6. To find out how much each friend should contribute, we divide the total by the number of friends (which is 3):\n   Contribution per friend = $98 ÷ 3 ≈ $32.67\n\nSo, each friend should pay approximately $32.67."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 3/5 answer="Let's break down the expenses:\n\n1. Tickets cost $20.25 and they bought 3 tickets, so they paid 3 * $20.25 = $<<3*20.25=60.75>>60.75\n\n2. Food costs $4.50 less than the tickets, which is $20.25 - $4.50 = $<<20.25-4.50=15.75>>\n\n3. They spent $33 on each of the 2 rides, so they spent 2 * $33 = $<<2*33=66>>66 on rides\n\nNow, let's find out what each person should pay if they shared the total costs evenly:\n\nTotal expenses: $60.75 + $15.75 + $66 = $<<60.75+15.75+66=142.5>>142.5\n\nNumber of people: 3 friends × 2 rides = 6 people\n\nCost per person: $142.5 ÷ 6 = $<<142.5/6=23.75>>23.75\n\nTherefore, each of the three friends should pay $23.75."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 4/5 answer='64'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 15/100 path 5/5 answer="To find out how much each friend paid, we first calculate the total amount spent on tickets:\nTotal cost of tickets = $20.25\n\nThen, we calculate the cost of food:\nCost of food = Total cost of tickets - $4.50 = $20.25 - $4.50 = $15.75\n\nNext, we calculate the total cost of rides:\nTotal cost of rides = Cost of food + (Number of rides × Cost per ride) = $15.75 + (2 × $33)\n\nNow, let's solve for the total cost of rides:\nTotal cost of rides = $15.75 + ($33 × 2)\nTotal cost of rides = $15.75 + $66\nTotal cost of rides = $81.75\n\nFinally, we divide the total cost of rides by the number of people (which is 3):\nAmount per person = Total cost of rides / Number of people = $81.75 / 3 = $27.25\n\nSo, each friend should pay $27.25."
