[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 23/100 path 4/5 answer='Susan works from 8 a.m. to 11 a.m., which is a total of 3 hours (8 am to 11 am). Since she stops for half an hour each time, we need to calculate the total time spent on breaks first, then subtract that from the total working time to find out the actual work time.\nTotal break time = 3 hours * 0.5 hours/minute = <<3*0.5=1.5>>1.5 minutes.\nNow we can calculate the actual work time:\nActual work time = Total working time - Break time = 3 hours - 1.5 minutes = 3 hours and 45 minutes - 1.5 minutes = <<3*60+45-15=195>>195 minutes.\nTo convert the work time into minutes:\nWork time = 195 minutes / 60 minutes/hour = <<195/60=3.25>>3.25 hours.\nSince she earns $5 every 10 minutes, we divide the total work time by 10 to get the number of 10-minute intervals:\nNumber of 10-minute intervals = Work time / 10 = <<3.25/10=0.325>>0.325 periods of 10 minutes.\nNow we multiply the number of periods by the hourly earning rate to find the total earnings:\nTotal earnings = Number of periods * Hourly earning rate = <<0.325*12=<<0.325*12=3.9>>3.9 dollars.\nTherefore, Betty earns $3.9 for the online task.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 23/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 23/100 path 5/5 answer="First, calculate the total time Susan spends on each part of her workday:\n- 11 a.m. to 1 p.m.: 1 p.m. - 11 a.m. = 13 hours\n- Half an hour before lunchtime: 1 hour\n- Lunch break: 1 hour\n- Half an hour after lunch: 1 hour\n\nNow, let's sum up the time spent working:\n- 13 hours (for the 13-hour period)\n- 1 hour (for the lunch break)\n- 1 hour (for the 1-hour period)\n\nTotal work time = 13 + 1 + 1 = 15 hours\n\nSince she earns $5 for every 10 minutes worked, we can find out how much she earns for the entire 15 hours:\n\nEarnings for 15 hours = 15 hours * ($5/hour) = $<15 * 5 = 75>.\n\nSusan needs $75 to complete the online task."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 23/100 done id=gsm8k_test_292 prediction='30' gold='75' correct=False vote_counts={'30': 1, '180': 1, '140': 1, 'Susan works from 8 a.m. to 11 a.m., which is a total of 3 hours (8 am to 11 am). Since she stops for half an hour each time, we need to calculate the total time spent on breaks first, then subtract that from the total working time to find out the actual work time.\nTotal break time = 3 hours * 0.5 hours/minute = <<3*0.5=1.5>>1.5 minutes.\nNow we can calculate the actual work time:\nActual work time = Total working time - Break time = 3 hours - 1.5 minutes = 3 hours and 45 minutes - 1.5 minutes = <<3*60+45-15=195>>195 minutes.\nTo convert the work time into minutes:\nWork time = 195 minutes / 60 minutes/hour = <<195/60=3.25>>3.25 hours.\nSince she earns $5 every 10 minutes, we divide the total work time by 10 to get the number of 10-minute intervals:\nNumber of 10-minute intervals = Work time / 10 = <<3.25/10=0.325>>0.325 periods of 10 minutes.\nNow we multiply the number of periods by the hourly earning rate to find the total earnings:\nTotal earnings = Number of periods * Hourly earning rate = <<0.325*12=<<0.325*12=3.9>>3.9 dollars.\nTherefore, Betty earns $3.9 for the online task.': 1, "First, calculate the total time Susan spends on each part of her workday:\n- 11 a.m. to 1 p.m.: 1 p.m. - 11 a.m. = 13 hours\n- Half an hour before lunchtime: 1 hour\n- Lunch break: 1 hour\n- Half an hour after lunch: 1 hour\n\nNow, let's sum up the time spent working:\n- 13 hours (for the 13-hour period)\n- 1 hour (for the lunch break)\n- 1 hour (for the 1-hour period)\n\nTotal work time = 13 + 1 + 1 = 15 hours\n\nSince she earns $5 for every 10 minutes worked, we can find out how much she earns for the entire 15 hours:\n\nEarnings for 15 hours = 15 hours * ($5/hour) = $<15 * 5 = 75>.\n\nSusan needs $75 to complete the online task.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 start id=gsm8k_test_318
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 1/5 answer='First, calculate the number of girls:\nNumber of girls = Number of boys × (3/10) = 30 × (3/10) = 9\n\nCalculate the total number of children including non-gendered ones:\nTotal children = Number of boys + Number of girls = 30 + 9 = 39\n\nSo, there are 39 children in total.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 2/5 answer="First, we determine the number of girls in the class based on the given ratio:\nNumber of girls = Number of boys × 3 = 30 × 3 = 90\n\nNext, we calculate the number of non-gendered children:\nNumber of non-gendered children = Number of boys / (1 + 1/10) = 30 / (1 + 1/10) = 30 / 1.1 ≈ 27.27\n\nSince we cannot have a fraction of a child, let's round down to the nearest whole number:\nNumber of non-gendered children = 27\n\nNow, we add up all the children:\nTotal children = Number of boys + Number of girls + Number of non-gendered children\nTotal children = 30 + 90 + 27 = 147\n\nSo the total number of children in the class is 147."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 3/5 answer='123'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 4/5 answer="Let's break down the information given:\n\n1. The number of boys in the classroom is 30.\n2. Since there are 3 times as many girls as boys, the number of girls is 30 * 3 = 90.\n3. There are 1/10 as many non-gendered children as boys, so the number of non-gendered children is 30 * 1/10 = 3.\n\nTo find the total number of children in the classroom:\n- Total children = Number of boys + Number of girls + Number of non-gendered children\n- Total children = 30 (boys) + 90 (girls) + 3 (non-gendered children)\n- Total children = 123\n\nSo, the total number of children in the classroom is 123."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 path 5/5 answer="Let G represent the number of girls and B represent the number of boys. We know that B = 30 (there are 30 boys) and G = 1/10 * B (there are 1/10 as many nongendered children as there are boys). Also, G + B = 30 + 30 = 60 (since the total number of boys and girls combined is 60).\n\nWe can find out how many nongendered children (which is G) using:\nG = 1/10 * B\n\nSubstituting B with 60 gives us:\nG = 1/10 * 60 = 6\n\nSo, we now know the number of both girls and boys:\nG = 6 (girls)\nB = 30 (boys)\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of children:\nTotal children = G + B = 6 + 30 = 36\n\nTherefore, the total number of children in the classroom is 36."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 24/100 done id=gsm8k_test_318 prediction='First, calculate the number of girls:\nNumber of girls = Number of boys × (3/10) = 30 × (3/10) = 9\n\nCalculate the total number of children including non-gendered ones:\nTotal children = Number of boys + Number of girls = 30 + 9 = 39\n\nSo, there are 39 children in total.' gold='123' correct=False vote_counts={'First, calculate the number of girls:\nNumber of girls = Number of boys × (3/10) = 30 × (3/10) = 9\n\nCalculate the total number of children including non-gendered ones:\nTotal children = Number of boys + Number of girls = 30 + 9 = 39\n\nSo, there are 39 children in total.': 1, "First, we determine the number of girls in the class based on the given ratio:\nNumber of girls = Number of boys × 3 = 30 × 3 = 90\n\nNext, we calculate the number of non-gendered children:\nNumber of non-gendered children = Number of boys / (1 + 1/10) = 30 / (1 + 1/10) = 30 / 1.1 ≈ 27.27\n\nSince we cannot have a fraction of a child, let's round down to the nearest whole number:\nNumber of non-gendered children = 27\n\nNow, we add up all the children:\nTotal children = Number of boys + Number of girls + Number of non-gendered children\nTotal children = 30 + 90 + 27 = 147\n\nSo the total number of children in the class is 147.": 1, '123': 1, "Let's break down the information given:\n\n1. The number of boys in the classroom is 30.\n2. Since there are 3 times as many girls as boys, the number of girls is 30 * 3 = 90.\n3. There are 1/10 as many non-gendered children as boys, so the number of non-gendered children is 30 * 1/10 = 3.\n\nTo find the total number of children in the classroom:\n- Total children = Number of boys + Number of girls + Number of non-gendered children\n- Total children = 30 (boys) + 90 (girls) + 3 (non-gendered children)\n- Total children = 123\n\nSo, the total number of children in the classroom is 123.": 1, "Let G represent the number of girls and B represent the number of boys. We know that B = 30 (there are 30 boys) and G = 1/10 * B (there are 1/10 as many nongendered children as there are boys). Also, G + B = 30 + 30 = 60 (since the total number of boys and girls combined is 60).\n\nWe can find out how many nongendered children (which is G) using:\nG = 1/10 * B\n\nSubstituting B with 60 gives us:\nG = 1/10 * 60 = 6\n\nSo, we now know the number of both girls and boys:\nG = 6 (girls)\nB = 30 (boys)\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of children:\nTotal children = G + B = 6 + 30 = 36\n\nTherefore, the total number of children in the classroom is 36.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 start id=gsm8k_test_326
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 1/5 answer="Let's break it down:\n\n- First, we start with 0 people because no one had boarded the bus yet.\n- At the first bus stop, 5 more people got in, so now we have \\(0 + 5 = 5\\) people on the bus.\n- Then, at the second bus stop, 7 people get down and 8 more get into the bus, resulting in \\(5 - 7 + 8 = 6\\) people on the bus.\n- Finally, if there were a total of 20 people going to the third stop, and 6 already boarded the bus, then \\(20 - 6 = 14\\) people got on the bus.\n\nSo, the number of people who got on the bus at the terminal is **14**."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 2/5 answer="To find out how many people got on the bus at the terminal, let's break it down step-by-step:\n\n1. Initially, there were 5 people getting on at the first bus stop.\n2. After the first stop, another 5 people got on because 5 + 5 = 10 people had already been on the bus before the first stop.\n3. So far, we have 5 (from the first stop) + 10 (after the first stop) = 15 people on the bus.\n\nAt the second bus stop:\n- 7 people got off because 5 + 7 = 12 people had already been on the bus before the second stop.\n- 8 more people got in because 15 + 8 = 23 people joined the bus.\n\nNow, we know that the total number of passengers was 20 (including those who got on or off at the two stops). Let’s denote the number of people who got on at the terminal as \\(x\\).\n\nFrom the above information, we can set up the following equation:\n\\[15 (people on the bus at the end of the first stop) + 7 (people who got off at the first stop) + x (people who got on at the second stop) + 8 (people who got in at the second stop) = 20 (total number of passengers)\n\nSimplifying this gives us:\n\\[15 + 7 + x + 8 = 20 \\]\n\nCombining like terms:\n\\[30 + x = 20 \\]\n\nSubtracting 30 from both sides:\n\\[x = 20 - 30 \\]\n\\[x = -10\\]\n\nIt seems we made an error in our calculation. We should subtract the people who left the bus when they got off at the first"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 3/5 answer='Let\'s break it down step-by-step:\n\n1. Initially, at the first bus stop, 5 more people got in.\n   So, we have 5 + initial passengers.\n\n2. At the second bus stop:\n   7 people get down and 8 more get in.\n   So, we subtract these numbers from the previous total.\n\n3. Total number of people going to the third stop is 20.\n\nTo find out how many people got on the bus initially (at the terminal), let\'s calculate step by step.\n\nInitial passengers: \n5 (from the first bus) + Initial passengers\n\nAfter the first stop:\n(5 + Initial passengers) - 7 (down) + 8 (in)\n\nAt the third stop with 20 people, the equation would look like this:\n\n(5 + Initial passengers) - 7 (down) + 8 (in) = 20\n\nNow, let\'s solve for "initial passengers":\n\n(5 + Initial passengers) = 20 + 7 + 8\n(5 + Initial passengers) = 35\n\nInitial passengers = 35 - 5\nInitial passengers = 30\n\nSo, 30 people got on the bus at the terminal.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 4/5 answer='Let \\( x \\) represent the number of people who initially got on the bus at the terminal. \n\nAt the first bus stop, 5 more people got in, so the total became \\( x + 5 \\).\n\nAt the second bus stop:\n- 7 people got off,\n- and 8 more got in,\nso the total becomes \\( (x + 5) - 7 + 8 \\).\n\nWe know from the problem statement that the total number of people heading to the third stop was 20. Therefore, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[\n(x + 5) - 7 + 8 = 20\n\\]\n\nSimplify and solve for \\( x \\):\n\n\\[\nx + 5 - 7 + 8 = 20\n\\]\n\\[\nx + 6 = 20\n\\]\n\\[\nx = 20 - 6\n\\]\n\\[\nx = 14\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the initial number of people who got on the bus at the terminal is **14**.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 5/5 answer='Let \\( x \\) represent the number of people who got on the bus at the terminal initially. We can set up the following equation based on the given information:\n\n\\( x + 5 + 7 - 8 = 20 \\)\n\nSimplifying the left side gives us:\n\n\\( x + 6 = 20 \\)\n\nSubtracting 6 from both sides gives us:\n\n\\( x = 14 \\)\n\nSo, the number of people who got on the bus at the terminal is 14.'
