[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 1/5 answer="First, let's find out the total number of guns:\nDJ has 8 guns,\nNick has 10 guns,\nRJ has 1 gun,\nRichard has 5 guns,\nTotal: 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = <<8+10+1+5=24>>24 guns.\n\nNext, we'll divide the total number of guns by the number of people (which is 5):\n24 guns ÷ 5 people = 4.8 guns/person.\n\nSince you can't split a gun into fractions, each person would get 4 full guns and 0.8 additional guns.\n\nSo, each person would have 4 full guns + 0.8 additional guns = 4.8 guns in total if shared equally."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 2/5 answer="To find out how many guns each person would have if they shared equally:\n- Total number of guns = DJ's guns + Nick's guns + RJ's guns + Richard's guns \n- Total number of guns = 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = 24\n\nSince there are 24 guns and they should be shared equally among themselves,\nEach person would get \\( \\frac{24}{4} = 6 \\) guns.\n\nSo, each of them would have 6 guns."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 3/5 answer="To find out how many guns each person would get if they shared them equally, we first need to determine the total number of guns and then divide that number by the number of people.\n\nTotal number of guns = 8 (DJ) + 10 (Nick) + 1 (RJ) + 5 (Richard)\n= 24\n\nNow, to share these guns equally among the five people:\n\nGuns per person = Total guns ÷ Number of people\n= 24 ÷ 5\n≈ 4.8\n\nSince it's not possible to split one gun into halves, we can say that each person would ideally receive 4 full guns and there would be some remaining guns left over, but it wouldn't be distributed further within the given constraints.\n\nIn summary:\n- Each person gets 4 full guns from the distribution.\n- There would still be 0.8 guns left over, which could potentially be divided or used differently depending on their preferences."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's calculate the total number of guns:\nDj (8 guns)\nNick (10 guns)\nRJ (1 gun)\nRichard (5 guns)\n\nTotal = 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = <<8+10+1+5=24>>24 guns\n\nNow, if they were to share these guns equally among themselves:\n\nEach person would get 24 / 5 = <<24/5=4.8>>4.8 guns\n\nSince we can't split a gun into fractions of a gun, we'll round down to the nearest whole number because you can't have a fraction of a gun for practical purposes.\n\nSo, each person would get 4 full guns and there will be 4.8 more guns left over.\n\nIn summary, each person would receive 4 guns and have 4.8 guns remaining, making it 5 full guns and still having 4.8 guns left over."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 27/100 path 5/5 answer='To determine how many guns each person gets when shared equally, we first calculate the total number of guns:\n\n- DJ has 8 guns,\n- Nick has 10 guns,\n- RJ has 1 gun,\n- Richard has 5 guns.\n\nAdding these together gives us:\n\\[ 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = 24 \\]\n\nSince there are four people sharing the guns (DJ, Nick, RJ, and Richard), we divide the total number of guns by 4 to find out how many guns each one gets:\n\\[ \\frac{24}{4} = 6 \\]\n\nSo each person would get 6 guns when shared equally.'
