lly receive 4 full guns and there would be some remaining guns left over, but it wouldn't be distributed further within the given constraints.\n\nIn summary:\n- Each person gets 4 full guns from the distribution.\n- There would still be 0.8 guns left over, which could potentially be divided or used differently depending on their preferences.": 1, "First, let's calculate the total number of guns:\nDj (8 guns)\nNick (10 guns)\nRJ (1 gun)\nRichard (5 guns)\n\nTotal = 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = <<8+10+1+5=24>>24 guns\n\nNow, if they were to share these guns equally among themselves:\n\nEach person would get 24 / 5 = <<24/5=4.8>>4.8 guns\n\nSince we can't split a gun into fractions of a gun, we'll round down to the nearest whole number because you can't have a fraction of a gun for practical purposes.\n\nSo, each person would get 4 full guns and there will be 4.8 more guns left over.\n\nIn summary, each person would receive 4 guns and have 4.8 guns remaining, making it 5 full guns and still having 4.8 guns left over.": 1, 'To determine how many guns each person gets when shared equally, we first calculate the total number of guns:\n\n- DJ has 8 guns,\n- Nick has 10 guns,\n- RJ has 1 gun,\n- Richard has 5 guns.\n\nAdding these together gives us:\n\\[ 8 + 10 + 1 + 5 = 24 \\]\n\nSince there are four people sharing the guns (DJ, Nick, RJ, and Richard), we divide the total number of guns by 4 to find out how many guns each one gets:\n\\[ \\frac{24}{4} = 6 \\]\n\nSo each person would get 6 guns when shared equally.': 1}
