[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 path 5/5 answer="To calculate the percentage of time spent editing, we first find out how long Carol spent on each task:\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours\n2. Recording: Half of 4 hours, so 4/2 = 2 hours\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, let's convert all times into a common unit (minutes) to make the calculation easier:\n\n- Writing: 4 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 240 minutes\n- Recording: 2 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 120 minutes\n- Editing: 90 minutes\n\nTotal time spent:\nWriting + Recording + Editing = 240 + 120 + 90 = 450 minutes\n\nNow, to find the percentage spent editing, we use the formula:\n\nPercentage spent editing = (Editing time / Total time) * 100%\n\nSo,\n\n(Editing time / Total time) * 100% = (90 / 450) * 100%\n= (1 / 5) * 100%\n= 20%\n\nTherefore, Carol spent 20% of her total work time editing the song."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 29/100 done id=gsm8k_test_393 prediction="To find out what percentage of her total work time Carol spent editing, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the time spent writing: 4 hours\n2. Calculate the time spent recording: Half the writing time, so 4 / 2 = 2 hours\n3. Convert the recording time from minutes to hours: 2 hours = 2 / 60 hours = 1 / 30 hours\n4. Add up all the times together: 4 + 2 + 1/30 = 4 + 2 + 1/30 ≈ 5.0333 hours (rounded to four decimal places)\n5. Calculate the percentage spent editing: (Editing time / Total time) * 100 = (90 / 5.0333) * 100 ≈ 179.37%\n\nTherefore, approximately 179.37% of her total work time was spent editing." gold='20' correct=False vote_counts={"To find out what percentage of her total work time Carol spent editing, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the time spent writing: 4 hours\n2. Calculate the time spent recording: Half the writing time, so 4 / 2 = 2 hours\n3. Convert the recording time from minutes to hours: 2 hours = 2 / 60 hours = 1 / 30 hours\n4. Add up all the times together: 4 + 2 + 1/30 = 4 + 2 + 1/30 ≈ 5.0333 hours (rounded to four decimal places)\n5. Calculate the percentage spent editing: (Editing time / Total time) * 100 = (90 / 5.0333) * 100 ≈ 179.37%\n\nTherefore, approximately 179.37% of her total work time was spent editing.": 1, '900': 1, '600': 1, '20': 1, "To calculate the percentage of time spent editing, we first find out how long Carol spent on each task:\n\n1. Writing: 4 hours\n2. Recording: Half of 4 hours, so 4/2 = 2 hours\n3. Editing: 90 minutes\n\nNow, let's convert all times into a common unit (minutes) to make the calculation easier:\n\n- Writing: 4 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 240 minutes\n- Recording: 2 hours * 60 minutes/hour = 120 minutes\n- Editing: 90 minutes\n\nTotal time spent:\nWriting + Recording + Editing = 240 + 120 + 90 = 450 minutes\n\nNow, to find the percentage spent editing, we use the formula:\n\nPercentage spent editing = (Editing time / Total time) * 100%\n\nSo,\n\n(Editing time / Total time) * 100% = (90 / 450) * 100%\n= (1 / 5) * 100%\n= 20%\n\nTherefore, Carol spent 20% of her total work time editing the song.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 start id=gsm8k_test_407
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 1/5 answer='1000'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 2/5 answer='To find out how many steps Elliott took during his jog, we first calculate the total number of steps he walked to and from school:\n- Steps to school: half of 10,000 = 10,000 / 2 = 5,000 steps\n- Steps from school: 1,000 steps\n\nAdding these together gives us the total steps taken before jogging:\n- Total steps taken: 5,000 + 1,000 = 6,000 steps\n\nAfter his jog, he had 2,000 steps remaining. To find out how many steps he took while jogging, we subtract the remaining steps from the total steps taken:\n- Steps during jog: 6,000 - 2,000 = 4,000 steps\n\nTherefore, Elliott took 4,000 steps during his jog.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 3/5 answer="Let's break it down step-by-step:\n\n1. Elliott walked to and from school and completed half of his total steps.\n   - Steps to and from school = 10,000 steps ÷ 2 = <<10000/2=5000>>5,000 steps\n\n2. After completing these two trips, he took another 1,000 steps going for a short walk with his friend.\n   - Additional steps = 1,000 steps\n\n3. Finally, he jogged around the block and realized he still had 2,000 steps remaining.\n   - Remaining steps = 2,000 steps\n\nNow let's calculate how many steps he took during his jog:\n   - Total steps taken (including jogging) = Initial steps + Additional steps + Remaining steps\n   - Total steps = 5,000 steps + 1,000 steps + 2,000 steps = 8,000 steps\n\nSo, Elliott took 8,000 steps during his jog."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 4/5 answer='First, we calculate the number of steps Elliott took to and from school:\n\\[ \\text{Steps to and from school} = 10,000 \\times \\frac{1}{2} = 5,000 \\]\nNext, we account for the additional 1,000 steps taken walking with his friend:\n\\[ \\text{Total steps before jogging} = 5,000 + 1,000 = 6,000 \\]\nFinally, we know that after finishing his jog, he had 2,000 steps left:\n\\[ \\text{Steps after jogging} = 6,000 - 2,000 = 4,000 \\]\nTherefore, the total number of steps Elliott took while jogging is 4,000.'
