[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 done id=gsm8k_test_440 prediction='246' gold='98' correct=False vote_counts={"To find the perimeter of the room, we first need to calculate the width using the area formula for a rectangle: Area = Length × Width. \n\nGiven:\nArea = 360 square feet\n\nLength = 3 yards = 18 feet (since there are 3 feet in a yard)\n\nUsing the area formula:\n\nWidth = Area ÷ Length\n   = 360 ÷ 18\n   = 20 feet\n\nNow, to get the perimeter, we can use the formula for the perimeter of a rectangle: Perimeter = 2 × (Length + Width).\n\nPerimeter = 2 × (18 + 20)\n         = 2 × 38\n         = 76 feet\n\nTherefore, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 76 feet.": 1, '246': 2, '92': 1, "First, let's find the width of the room. We know the area (A) and the length (L), so we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle:\n\n\\[ A = L \\times W \\]\n\nGiven:\n\\( A = 360 \\) square feet\n\\( L = 3 \\) yards\n\nWe need to convert the length from yards to feet. Since there are 3 feet in a yard, \\( L \\) would be:\n\n\\( L_{\\text{feet}} = 3 \\text{ yards} \\times 3 \\frac{\\text{feet}}{\\text{yard}} = 9 \\text{ feet} \\)\n\nNow we can solve for the width \\( W \\):\n\n\\( 360 = 9 \\times W \\)\n\\( W = \\frac{360}{9} \\)\n\\( W = 40 \\) feet\n\nNext, we can calculate the perimeter \\( P \\) using the formula:\n\n\\[ P = 2 \\times (\\text{length} + \\text{width}) \\]\n\nSo:\n\n\\[ P = 2 \\times (3 \\text{ feet} + 40 \\text{ feet}) \\]\n\\[ P = 2 \\times 43 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\\[ P = 86 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nTherefore, the perimeter of the room is 86 feet.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 start id=gsm8k_test_447
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 1/5 answer="First, we calculate how many points Joey will have after his turn:\nJoey's score + 26 = 214 + 26 = 240\n\nThen, we account for Marcy's contribution:\nMarcy's total score + Marcy's additional points = 225 + 10 = 235\n\nNow we find the difference between Joey's final score and Marcy's final score:\nJoey's final score - Marcy's final score = 240 - 235 = 5\n\nTherefore, Joey is now winning by 5 points."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 2/5 answer='To determine how many points Joey is now winning, we first calculate the net increase in points for both Joey and Marcy. \n\nJoey starts with 214 points but loses 26 points during his turn:\n\\[ 214 - 26 = 188 \\text{ points} \\]\n\nMarcy initially has 225 points and increases it by 10 points:\n\\[ 225 + 10 = 235 \\text{ points} \\]\n\nNow, we find the difference between Joey’s current score and Marcy’s score:\n\\[ 188 - 235 = -47 \\text{ points} \\]\n\nTherefore, Joey is now losing 47 points compared to Marcy.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 3/5 answer="First, we find out how many more points Joey has than Marcy before their respective turns:\nJoey's points before his turn = 214\nMarcy's initial score = 225\n\nDifference in points between Joey and Marcy before their turn = 214 - 225 = -11 points\n\nJoey's current total points = 214 (before) + 26 (after) = 240 points\n\nBy subtracting the difference from Joey's current total points, we get:\nDifference by how many points Joey is now winning = 240 - (-11) = 240 + 11 = 251 points"
