[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 2/5 answer='First, calculate how much Becky paid for her apples without the discount:\nBecky paid 20 * $0.45 = $<<20*0.45=9>>9 for the apples.\nAfter the $1 discount, Becky paid $9 - $1 = $<<9-1=8>>8.\n\nNext, calculate how much Kelly paid for her apples without the discount:\nKelly paid 20 * $0.50 = $<<20*0.50=10>>10 for the apples.\nWith a 10% discount, Kelly paid 10 * (1 - 0.10) = $10 * 0.90 = $<<10*0.90=9>>9.\n\nFinally, find out how much more Kelly paid compared to Becky:\n$9 - $8 = $<<9-8=1>>1.\n\nSo, Kelly paid $1 more than Becky.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 39/100 path 3/5 answer="To determine how much more Kelly paid compared to Becky, we first calculate their individual total payments:\n\nFor Becky:\nBecky spent 20 apples at 45 cents each. Therefore, her total cost before the discount was \\(20 \\times 45\\). After applying the $1 discount, her net payment is \\(20 \\times 45 - 1\\).\n\nFor Kelly:\nKelly purchased 20 apples at 50 cents each. Thus, her total cost before the discount is \\(20 \\times 50\\). With a 10% discount on her total purchase, her net payment is calculated as follows:\n\n\\[ \\text{Net Payment} = 20 \\times 50 - (10\\% \\times (20 \\times 50)) \\]\n\nNow let's compute these values:\n\n### Becky's Calculation:\n\\[ 20 \\times 45 = 900 \\]\n\\[ 900 - 1 = 899 \\]\n\n### Kelly's Calculation:\n\\[ 20 \\times 50 = 1000 \\]\n\\[ 1000 - (0.1 \\times 1000) = 1000 - 100 = 900 \\]\n\nSince the problem asks how much more Kelly paid than Becky, we subtract the amount Becky paid from the amount Kelly paid:\n\n\\[ 900 - 899 = 1 \\]\n\nTherefore, Kelly paid $1 more than Becky."
