[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 43/100 path 2/5 answer="To determine how many popsicle sticks Frederick can make with the given budget, we'll calculate the cost of using each type of wood separately and see what combinations will allow him to buy all the required sticks without exceeding his budget.\n\nFirst, let's calculate the cost of buying wood for each size of stick:\n- A 2 x 4 piece of wood costs $4.\n- A 2 x 8 piece of wood costs $6.\n\nNext, we'll find out how many 2 x 4 pieces and 2 x 8 pieces of wood are needed:\n- To get 200 sticks from a 2 x 4 piece: \\( \\frac{200}{200} = 1 \\) 2 x 4 piece\n- To get 200 sticks from a 2 x 8 piece: \\( \\frac{200}{200} = 1 \\) 2 x 8 piece\n\nNow, let's figure out how many complete sets of these pieces he can buy:\n- 1 2 x 4 piece gives us 1 set (4 sticks)\n- 1 2 x 8 piece gives us 1 set (8 sticks)\n\nSince each set requires one 2 x 4 piece and one 2 x 8 piece, we have enough wood for:\n- 4 2 x 4 pieces\n- 8 2 x 8 pieces\n\nWith the 4 2 x 4 pieces, he gets:\n- \\( 4 \\times 200 = 800 \\) sticks\n\nAnd with the 8 2 x 8 pieces, he gets:\n- \\( 8 \\times 200 = 1600 \\) sticks\n\nSo far, he has used up \\( 4 + 8 = 12 \\) sticks"
