0 sticks\n\nSince he can only use whole sticks at a time without leftovers, he'll have to make 6 sets of either 200 or 400 sticks.\n\nWith 200 sticks per set (from both types), he could make 6 * 200 = <<6*200=1200>>1200 sticks.\nWith 400 sticks per set (again, from both types), he could make 6 * 400 = <<": 1, "First, let's calculate the cost of each type of wood:\n- A 2 x 4 piece of wood costs $4.\n- A 2 x 8 piece of wood costs $6.\nNext, we'll determine how many popsicle sticks Frederick can get with each type of wood:\n- From the 2 x 4 piece of wood, he gets 200/400 = 1/2 stick per unit (since it's cheaper).\n- From the 2 x 8 piece of wood, he gets 400/900 = 4/9 sticks per unit.\nNow, we'll calculate how many complete units of each wood he can buy with his $24 budget:\n- With $24, he can buy 24 / 4 = 6 units of 2 x 4 pieces.\n- With $24, he can buy 24 / 6 = 4 units of 2 x 8 pieces.\nFinally, we'll calculate how many popsicle sticks he can make with these units:\n- With 6 units of 2 x 4 pieces, he can make 6 * 1/2 = 3 sticks.\n- With 4 units of 2 x 8 pieces, he can make 4 * 4/9 ≈ 1.33 times the original amount, so he can make approximately 5.33 sticks per unit.\nSince he can't have a fraction of a stick, he can make a total of 5 sticks from the 2 x 8 piece of wood, but since he can't have less than 1 stick, he will make 5 sticks from the 2 x 4 piece of wood.\nTo find out the maximum number of sticks he can make, we'll take the minimum value between the two calculations: 1 (from": 1, "To determine how many popsicle sticks Frederick can make with his given budget and lumber types, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. **Determine the cost of each type of wood**:\n    - A 2 x 4 piece of wood costs $4.\n    - A 2 x 8 piece of wood costs $6.\n\n2. **Calculate the total number of sticks available from each type of wood**:\n    - For 2 x 4 pieces:\n        \\[\n        200 \\text{ (from a 2 x 4 piece)} \\div 4 = 50 \\text{ sticks}\n        \\]\n    - For 2 x 8 pieces:\n        \\[\n        400 \\text{ (from a 2 x 8 piece)} \\div 8 = 50 \\text{ sticks}\n        \\]\n\n3. **Identify the cheapest lumber**:\n    - Comparing the two options, both offer the same amount of wood:\n        - 2 x 4 pieces: $4\n        - 2 x 8 pieces: $6\n\n4. **Make the decision based on the cheaper option**:\n    - Since neither type of wood provides a significant advantage in terms of price or quantity compared to using one stick from either type, Frederick should choose to buy sticks from either the 2 x 4 or the 2 x 8 piece.\n\n5. **Calculate the maximum number of sticks Frederick can make**:\n    - Using the 2 x 4 piece wood:\n        \\[\n        200 \\text{ sticks} \\div 4 = 50 \\text{ sticks}\n        \\]\n    - Using the 2 x 8 piece wood:\n        \\[\n        400 \\text{ sticks} \\div 8 = 50 \\text{ sticks}": 1}
