[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 1/5 answer='First, calculate the age difference between the two sons:\n- Older son: 12 years old\n- Younger son: 4 years younger than older son, so 12 - 4 = 8 years old\n\nNow, determine how many packs of candles James needs:\n- Each pack contains 5 candles\n- He needs 5 packs because he wants to have enough candles for both sons\n\nCalculate the total number of candles needed:\n- Total candles = 5 packs * 5 candles/pack = 25 candles\n\nCalculate how many packs James actually buys with $3 (since each pack costs $3):\n- Since each pack costs $3 and James has $3 left over ($3 < $3), he can buy all the packs without spending more money.\n\nThus, James spends 25 candles on candles.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 2/5 answer='First, find out how old the other son is: he is 4 years younger than the first one, so 12 - 4 = 8 years old. Now calculate the number of packs needed: since each pack contains 5 candles, divide 20 (the total number of candles) by 5 to get 4 packs. Each pack costs $3, so multiply 4 packs by $3 to get $12. Therefore, James spends $12 on candles.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/5 answer="First, calculate how old the second son is: 12 + 4 = 16 years old. \nSo, there are two packs needed (one for each son): 16 / 5 = 3.2 packs. Since you can't get a fraction of a pack, we round up to 4 packs (since you'd need at least one full pack).\nEach pack costs $3, so he spends: 4 * $3 = $<<4*3=12>>12. \nTherefore, James spends $12 on candles."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's calculate how old each son is:\n\nSon 1 (who is 12):\nSon 1's age = 12\n\nSon 2 (who is 4 years younger):\nSon 2's age = 12 - 4 = 8\n\nNext, we'll find out how many packs of candles James needs to buy:\n\nNumber of packs needed = Total number of candles ÷ Number of candles per pack\n                            = (2 × 12) ÷ 5\n                            = 24 ÷ 5\n                            ≈ 4.8\n\nSince you can't buy a fraction of a pack, James will need to buy 5 packs to have enough candles for both sons.\n\nNow, we calculate how much James spends:\n\nTotal cost = Number of packs × Cost per pack\n            = 5 × $3\n            = $15\n\nSo, James spends $15 on candles. The final answer is 15."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 5/5 answer='First, we determine how old the first son is. Since he is 4 years younger than the second son, he is 4 + 12 = 16 years old. \n\nNext, we calculate the total number of candles needed:\n- For the older son (16 years old): 16 candles\n- For the younger son (4 years old): 4 candles\n\nSo, the total number of candles required is 16 + 4 = 20 candles.\n\nNow, we calculate the cost:\n- Each pack contains 5 candles.\n- There are 2 packs needed.\n\nThus, James needs 2 packs × 5 candles/pack = 10 packs of candles.\n\nFinally, we compute the total amount spent:\n- Total cost = Number of packs × Cost per pack = 10 packs × $3/pack = $30.\n\nTherefore, James spends $30 on candles.'
