 get a fraction of a pack, we round up to 4 packs (since you'd need at least one full pack).\nEach pack costs $3, so he spends: 4 * $3 = $<<4*3=12>>12. \nTherefore, James spends $12 on candles.": 1, "First, let's calculate how old each son is:\n\nSon 1 (who is 12):\nSon 1's age = 12\n\nSon 2 (who is 4 years younger):\nSon 2's age = 12 - 4 = 8\n\nNext, we'll find out how many packs of candles James needs to buy:\n\nNumber of packs needed = Total number of candles ÷ Number of candles per pack\n                            = (2 × 12) ÷ 5\n                            = 24 ÷ 5\n                            ≈ 4.8\n\nSince you can't buy a fraction of a pack, James will need to buy 5 packs to have enough candles for both sons.\n\nNow, we calculate how much James spends:\n\nTotal cost = Number of packs × Cost per pack\n            = 5 × $3\n            = $15\n\nSo, James spends $15 on candles. The final answer is 15.": 1, 'First, we determine how old the first son is. Since he is 4 years younger than the second son, he is 4 + 12 = 16 years old. \n\nNext, we calculate the total number of candles needed:\n- For the older son (16 years old): 16 candles\n- For the younger son (4 years old): 4 candles\n\nSo, the total number of candles required is 16 + 4 = 20 candles.\n\nNow, we calculate the cost:\n- Each pack contains 5 candles.\n- There are 2 packs needed.\n\nThus, James needs 2 packs × 5 candles/pack = 10 packs of candles.\n\nFinally, we compute the total amount spent:\n- Total cost = Number of packs × Cost per pack = 10 packs × $3/pack = $30.\n\nTherefore, James spends $30 on candles.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 start id=gsm8k_test_569
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 1/5 answer="To determine how much more money Mitchell made compared to Liam, we'll first calculate their earnings separately:\n\n**Liam's Earnings:**\nLiam made $63 when he was standing out from his friend and selling lemonade with his brother. To find out how much money he earned per stand, we divide his total earnings by the number of stands:\n\\[ \\text{Earnings per stand} = \\frac{\\$63}{2} = \\$31.50 \\]\n\nSince there were two stands (with Liam), the total amount Liam made for the weekend would be:\n\\[ \\text{Total earnings for Liam} = \\$31.50 \\times 2 = \\$63 \\]\n\nNow, let's calculate Mitchell's earnings:\nMitchell sold 21 lemonades at $4 each, so:\n\\[ \\text{Earnings for Mitchell} = 21 \\times \\$4 = \\$84 \\]\n\nFinally, we subtract Liam’s earnings from Mitchell's earnings to find out how much more they made:\n\\[ \\text{Difference} = \\$84 - \\$63 = \\$\\$21 \\]\n\nSo, Mitchell made $21 more than Liam in that weekend."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 2/5 answer='21'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 51/100 path 3/5 answer="First, let's calculate how much money each person made:\n\nLiam made $63.\n\nMitchell made $21 (which is 21 * $4) selling lemonade.\n\nNow we subtract Liam's earnings from Mitchell's earnings to find out how much more Mitchell made:\n\n$21 ($21) - $63 ($63) = -$42.\n\nSince we're looking for how much more Mitchell made compared to Liam, we take the absolute value of the result:\n\n|-$42| = $42.\n\nTherefore, Mitchell made $42 more than Liam that weekend."
