[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 56/100 path 5/5 answer="To determine how many new recipes John learns, we'll break down the information given:\n\n1. John attends the cooking class 4 times a week for 2 hours each session.\n2. The class meets for 6 weeks.\n3. Each session lasts 2 hours.\n4. He learns one new recipe for every 1.5 hours of class time.\n\nFirst, let's calculate the total number of hours John spends in class:\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = \\text{Number of sessions per week} \\times \\text{Hours per session} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = 4 \\times 2 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = 8 \\]\n\nNext, since he learns one new recipe for every 1.5 hours of class time, we can find the number of recipes by dividing the total number of hours by 1.5:\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{\\text{Total hours}}{1.5} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{8}{1.5} \\]\n\nLet's simplify this fraction to get the exact number of recipes:\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{8}{1.5} \\approx 5.33 \\]\n\nSince John can't learn a fraction of a recipe, we round up to the nearest whole number (as you cannot learn a partial recipe):\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = 6 \\]\n\nTherefore, John learns **6** new recipes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 56/100 done id=gsm8k_test_664 prediction='32' gold='32' correct=True vote_counts={'32': 4, "To determine how many new recipes John learns, we'll break down the information given:\n\n1. John attends the cooking class 4 times a week for 2 hours each session.\n2. The class meets for 6 weeks.\n3. Each session lasts 2 hours.\n4. He learns one new recipe for every 1.5 hours of class time.\n\nFirst, let's calculate the total number of hours John spends in class:\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = \\text{Number of sessions per week} \\times \\text{Hours per session} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = 4 \\times 2 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total hours} = 8 \\]\n\nNext, since he learns one new recipe for every 1.5 hours of class time, we can find the number of recipes by dividing the total number of hours by 1.5:\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{\\text{Total hours}}{1.5} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{8}{1.5} \\]\n\nLet's simplify this fraction to get the exact number of recipes:\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = \\frac{8}{1.5} \\approx 5.33 \\]\n\nSince John can't learn a fraction of a recipe, we round up to the nearest whole number (as you cannot learn a partial recipe):\n\\[ \\text{Number of recipes} = 6 \\]\n\nTherefore, John learns **6** new recipes.": 1}
