[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 57/100 path 2/5 answer="To find out how much Manolo paid for the candies, we can subtract the total cost of the lollipops from the given total cost:\nTotal cost of lollipops = Cost per lollipop × Number of lollipops = $0.40 × 5 = $<<0.40*5=2>>2\n\nNow, if he had paid the full amount for the lollipops (which would have been 5 × $0.40), we can calculate the remaining amount for the candies:\nRemaining amount for candies = Total cost - Cost of lollipops = $3.20 - $2 = $<<3.20-2=1.20>>\n\nNext, we'll determine the cost for 10 lollipops and 10 candies:\nCost for 10 lollipops = Cost per lollipop × Number of lollipops = $0.40 × 10 = $<<0.40*10=4>>4\nCost for 10 candies = Cost per candy × Number of candies = $0.60 × 10 = $<<0.60*10=6>>6\n\nFinally, adding these two amounts together gives us the total cost:\nTotal cost = Cost for 10 lollipops + Cost for 10 candies = $4 + $6 = $<<4+6=10>>10\n\nTherefore, 10 lollipops and 10 candies will cost Manolo $10."
