[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 3/5 answer="To determine how much money the vendor saves in a week, let's break down the problem into smaller steps:\n\n1. **Daily Sales Revenue**:\n   - The vendor sells 500 tomatoes daily.\n   - The vendor buys each tomato at $0.50.\n   - Therefore, daily revenue from buying tomatoes = \\( 500 \\text{ tomatoes/day} \\times \\$0.50/\\text{tomato} = \\$250/\\text{day} \\).\n\n2. **New Vendor Prices**:\n   - The new vendor buys tomatoes for $0.40 each.\n   - Since the vendor uses to buy at $0.50, there is a profit potential.\n\n3. **Weekly Total Revenue**:\n   - Weekly sales will occur over 7 days.\n   - Weekly total revenue without considering the new vendor would be \\( 500 \\text{ tomatoes/day} \\times \\$0.50/\\text{tomato} \\).\n     \\( 500 \\times \\$0.50 = \\$250 \\).\n\n4. **Profit Calculation**:\n   - After accounting for the cost of buying tomatoes (which increases weekly), we can calculate the net profit.\n   - Net profit per day = Weekly revenue - Daily purchase price.\n     \\( \\$250 - \\$250 = \\$0 \\) (no change in net profit since no additional cost or revenue comes from selling the tomatoes).\n\nTherefore, Betty does not save any money in a week because even though the new vendor offers a higher price, they increase their total revenue by $0 due to the increased cost of purchasing tomatoes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 63/100 path 4/5 answer='To determine how much money the vendor saves a week, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the cost of buying the tomatoes at the new price:\n   - Original price per tomato: $0.50\n   - New price per tomato: $0.40\n   \n   Cost savings from buying tomatoes:\n   \\[\n   (0.40 - 0.50) \\times 500 = -0.10 \\times 500 = -50\n   \\]\n   \n2. Convert daily savings to weekly savings:\n   \\[\n   50 \\text{ dollars/day} \\times 7 \\text{ days/week} = 350 \\text{ dollars/week}\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the vendor saves **$350** in a week.'
