[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 1/5 answer="To determine how many additional students joined the campus during the given period, we'll follow these steps:\n\n1. **Identify Initial Conditions**:\n   - Number of students initially (at the beginning of the year): 10\n\n2. **Determine Monthly Growth Rate**:\n   - Since the number of students doubles each month, we can calculate the growth rate using exponential growth formula:\n     \\[\n     N(t) = N_0 \\times 2^{t-1}\n     \\]\n     where \\(N(t)\\) is the number of students at time \\(t\\), \\(N_0\\) is the initial number of students, and \\(t\\) is the time measured in months.\n\n3. **Calculate Annual Growth Rate**:\n   - At the end of the first month (\\(t=1\\)):\n     \\[\n     N(1) = 10 \\times 2^0 = 10\n     \\]\n\n4. **Calculate Additional Students by End of May**:\n   - From the second month onward, students double each month.\n   - Calculate the number of students up to June:\n     \\[\n     N(2) = 10 \\times 2^1 = 20\n     \\]\n   - Calculate the number of students between July and August:\n     \\[\n     N(3) = 20 \\times 2^1 = 40\n     \\]\n   - Calculate the number of students up to September:\n     \\[\n     N(4) = 40 \\times 2^1 = 80\n     \\]\n\n5. **Total Additional Students from May to October**:\n   - Sum up all the additional students from May to October:\n     \\[\n     20 + 40 + 80 = 140\n     \\]\n\nTherefore, by the"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 2/5 answer='To find out how many additional students joined by the end of May, we first calculate the total number of students over the course of the year. We know that the number of students doubles each month from January to June, and then doubles again from July to December.\n\n1. From January to March (3 months), the number of students doubles once:\n   \\( 10 \\times 2^3 = 10 \\times 8 = 80 \\) students\n\n2. From April to June (3 months), the number of students doubles once more:\n   \\( 80 \\times 2 = 160 \\) students\n\n3. For July, August, and September (3 months), the number of students doubles once more:\n   \\( 160 \\times 2 = 320 \\) students\n\n4. For October through December (3 months), the number of students doubles once more:\n   \\( 320 \\times 2 = 640 \\) students\n\nNow we sum up all these numbers to get the total number of students over the entire year:\n   \\( 80 + 160 + 320 + 640 = 1200 \\)\n\nSo, by the end of May, there were 1200 additional students on campus compared to the initial count of 10 students.\n\nTherefore, the number of additional students who would join by the end of May, above and beyond the number of students already on campus at the beginning of the year, is **1200**.'
