rritos} = 12 - 20 = -8 \\]\n\nHowever, since it's not possible to have negative burritos, we can see that Mr. George didn't eat enough burritos or the class couldn't cover all the students with the available burritos, so there would still be some left over. Let's break down the calculation to confirm this:\nIf the class had enough burritos but didn't manage to feed everyone (since they can't have negative burritos), the remaining would simply be 0 because the full group cannot be fed without leftovers. But since the question asks specifically about what remains when all were fully eaten, let's correct our understanding:\n\nSince 12 burritos were given to the students and Mr. George ate 20, he must have eaten less than the full set of burritos required to feed all 50 students. Thus, the remainder represents the amount of leftover burritos if no additional burritos were provided. \n\nSo, Mr. George ate \\(12 + 20 = 32\\) burritos, meaning there should be \\(600 - 32 = 568\\) remaining burritos that would have been fed to the students if there hadn't been any overlap.": 1, 'First, we determine the total number of burritos given out to the students:\nNumber of students = 50\nBurritos per student = 10\n\nTotal burritos given out = Number of students × Burritos per student = 50 × 10 = 500 burritos\n\nNext, we account for Mr. George’s consumption:\nMr. George ate 20 burritos\n\nLeftover burritos = Total given-out burritos - Mr. George’s consumption = 500 - 20 = 480 burritos\n\nSo the total number of leftover burritos is 480.': 1, '100': 1}
