[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 1/5 answer="First, let's find out how many words Craig's brother spelled out:\n\nSince he started with 20 words with 15 letters each and had spells that were 50 letters longer than Craig's words, we can subtract 10 from the initial word count (since we don't know the exact number yet) to get the number of additional words he added:\n\n20 words - 10 words = 10 words\n\nNow, let's add these to the 15-letter words Craig initially spelled out:\n\n15 words + 10 words = 25 words\n\nCraig's brother's total spellings will include these 25 words plus the additional 10 words, giving us:\n\n25 words + 10 words = 35 words\n\nNext, we'll look at the brothers' counts of letters per word:\n\nCRAZIE: 8 letters per word\nANDY: 7 letters per word\nJACK: 9 letters per word\nTOM: 10 letters per word\n\nAdding up the letters per word:\n\n8 + 7 + 9 + 10 = 34 letters\n\nSo, Craig's brother has spelled out 35 words, but they have also added letters to each of those words based on their individual letter counts. We already accounted for the 10 letters per word, so we add them back to the total:\n\n35 words * 34 letters per word = 1190 letters\n\nTherefore, Craig's brother has spelled out a total of 1190 letters in all."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 2/5 answer="To solve this problem, we first need to understand how many letters are used in the words spelled out by both Craig and his brother over ten rounds. We start by calculating the number of letters used in one round:\n- Craig spells out 20 words (with 15 letters each) so he uses \\(20 \\times 15 = 300\\) letters.\n- His brother spells out \\(n\\) words (where \\(n > 20\\)) so he uses \\(n \\times 50\\) letters (since he adds 50 letters to every word).\n\nNow, let's assume he has spelled out \\(x\\) words (more than 20 but less than or equal to 20). This would mean he has \\(x\\) words with 50 letters each, using \\(50x\\) letters in total. Since his brother also has \\(x\\) words, he would have \\(nx + 50x\\) letters in total. We can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ 300 + nx = n(50x) \\]\n\nWe also know from the problem statement that his brother has 50 more letters than Craig, so we can write:\n\n\\[ nx + 50x = 300 \\]\n\\[ nx = 250 \\]\n\nSince \\(n > 20\\), let's substitute \\(n = 250/x\\) into the equation above. However, since the exact value of \\(x\\) isn't given, we can still find the relationship between the total letters used by both brothers.\n\nLet's solve for \\(x\\) in terms of \\(n\\):\n\n\\[ nx = 250 \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{250}{n} \\]\n\nSubstituting \\(x = \\frac{250}{n}\\) back into the original equation"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 3/5 answer="Craig initially had 15 letters each of the first 9 rounds, so he spent 9 * 15 = 135 letters.\nAfter ten rounds, Craig will have spent a total of 10 * 15 = 150 letters.\nIf Craig's brother has spelled words with a total count of letters 50 more than Craig, then his total spellings would have been 150 + 50 = 200 letters.\nSo, the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds would be 135 (Craig) + 200 (brother) = <<135+200=335>>335 letters."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 4/5 answer="Firstly, we need to determine how many letters Craig and his brother have spelled out in their respective games so far. For Craig:\nHe has played for 10 rounds and spells out words with 15 letters each. So, in round 10 he would have spelled out 10 x 15 = 150 letters. Since he had already spelled 20 letters in the first round, he will have spelled out 150 + 20 = 170 letters in total across all ten rounds.\nFor his brother:\nHe has played for 10 rounds and spells out words with 50 more letters than Craig. This means he spells out 150 + 50 = 200 letters each in these ten rounds. Since his brother started at 20 letters, he will have spelled out 200 x 10 = 2000 letters in total across all ten rounds.\n\nTo find the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds, we simply add the total letters from both Craig and his brother:\n\nTotal letters in words = Total letters from Craig + Total letters from brother\nTotal letters in words = 170 (Craig) + 2000 (brother)\nTotal letters in words = 2170\n\nSo, the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds is 2170."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 75/100 path 5/5 answer="First, let's determine how many letters Craig's brother spelled. Since he had 50 more letters than Craig, we subtract 50 from the total letters spelled by Craig:\n\nCraig: 20 words * 15 letters/word = 300 letters\nBrother: 300 letters (Craig) + 50 letters = 350 letters\n\nNow, we'll sum up the letters spelled by both Craig and his brother over the ten rounds:\n\nTotal letters = Craig's words + Brother's words\nTotal letters = 300 letters (Craig) + 350 letters (Brother)\nTotal letters = 650 letters\n\nSo, the total number of letters in the words they've spelled after the ten rounds is 650."
