[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 2/5 answer="To find out how many children can stand in the drills, we need to multiply the number of schools by the number of rows and then by the number of children per row. This gives us:\n\nNumber of children = Number of schools × Number of rows × Number of children per row\n\nGiven:\n- Number of schools = 7\n- Number of rows = 8\n- Number of children per row = 5\n\nLet's calculate:\n\nNumber of children = 7 × 8 × 5\nNumber of children = 56 × 5\nNumber of children = 280\n\nTherefore, the number of children that can participate in the drills is 280."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 76/100 path 3/5 answer='To find out how many children can be in the drill, we need to multiply the number of rows by the number of schools in each row and then by the total number of schools.\n\nSo, if there are 7 rows, with each row holding 5 schools, we get:\n\n7 rows × 5 schools/row = 35 schools\n\nTherefore, there can be 35 children in the drill.'
