\[ \\text{Bakery} = 525 - 40 \\]\n\n\\[ \\text{Bakery} = 485 \\]\n\nSo, the bakery has": 1, '450': 1, 'First, calculate seven times the number of loaves Sam had last Friday. That would be 7 * 70 = <<7*70=490>>490 loaves.\nNext, add ten to get the total number of loaves the bakery has. This would be 490 + 40 = <<490+40=530>>530 loaves.\nTherefore, the bakery has 530 loaves of bread.': 1, 'To determine the total number of loaves of bread the bakery has, we first need to find out how many loaves of bread Sam initially had last Friday. According to the problem, Sam had 70 loaves of bread last Friday. \n\nGiven that the bakery has 40 less than seven times as many loaves of bread as Sam had last Friday, we can calculate the number of loaves the bakery has as follows:\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves the bakery has} = 7 \\times (\\text{Number of loaves Sam had}) + 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves the bakery has} = 7 \\times 70 + 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves the bakery has} = 490 + 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves the bakery has} = 530 \\]\n\nSo, the bakery has 530 loaves of bread.': 1}
