[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 4/5 answer='Let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals Teresa sold and \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold. According to the problem:\n\n1. Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones:\n   \\[\n   S = 2L\n   \\]\n\n2. Let \\( C_L \\) represent the cost of each large stuffed animal and \\( C_S \\) represent the cost of each small stuffed animal:\n   \\[\n   C_L = \\$4\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   C_S = 3C_L = 3 \\times 4 = \\$12\n   \\]\n\n3. Given that Teresa earned $120 from the sale of all the stuffed animals, we can set up the equation:\n   \\[\n   L \\cdot C_L + S \\cdot C_S = 120\n   \\]\n   Substituting the known values:\n   \\[\n   L \\times 4 + S \\times 12 = 120\n   \\]\n\n4. Substitute \\( S = 2L \\) into the equation:\n   \\[\n   L \\times 4 + 2L \\times 12 = 120\n   \\]\n\n5. Simplify the equation:\n   \\[\n   4L + 24L = 120\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   28L = 120\n   \\]\n\n6. Solve for \\( L \\):\n   \\[\n   L = \\frac{120}{28} = \\frac{30}{7} \\approx 4.29\n   \\]\n\nSince the number of large stuffed animals must be a whole number:\n   \\[\n   L \\text{ (rounded)} = 4\n   \\]\n\n7. Using \\( L = 4 \\'
