[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 80/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1093 prediction="To find out how much it will cost to paint the room, we first calculate the total area of all the walls, then subtract the areas of the already painted sections (the windows).\n\nStep 1: Calculate the total area of the walls.\nNorth wall: \\(10 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nSouth wall: \\(10 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nEast wall: \\(5 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nWest wall: \\(5 \\times 8\\) sq ft\n\nTotal area = North + South + East + West\n\nStep 2: Subtract the areas of the windows from the total wall area to get the uncovered area.\nLet's assume there are two windows on each wall, so we'll need to subtract 2 sq ft per window to account for them.\n\nStep 3: Calculate the remaining uncovered area.\nUncovered area = Total area - Windows covered\n\nNow let's do the math:\n\nStep 1:\n\\(10 \\times 8 = 80\\) sq ft\n\\(10 \\times 8 = 80\\) sq ft\n\\(5 \\times 8 = 40\\) sq ft\n\\(5 \\times 8 = 40\\) sq ft\n\nTotal area = 80 + 80 + 40 + 40 = 240 sq ft\n\nStep 2:\n(80 + 40) - (2 * 2)\n= 120 - 4\n= 116 sq ft\n\nStep 3:\n116 sq ft - 2 sq ft (windows covered) = 114 sq ft uncovered\n\nTherefore, the cost would be \\(114 \\text{ sq ft} / 20 \\text{ sq ft/gallon} = 5.70 \\text{ gallons}\\). \n\nCost" gold='144' correct=False vote_counts={"To find out how much it will cost to paint the room, we first calculate the total area of all the walls, then subtract the areas of the already painted sections (the windows).\n\nStep 1: Calculate the total area of the walls.\nNorth wall: \\(10 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nSouth wall: \\(10 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nEast wall: \\(5 \\times 8\\) sq ft\nWest wall: \\(5 \\times 8\\) sq ft\n\nTotal area = North + South + East + West\n\nStep 2: Subtract the areas of the windows from the total wall area to get the uncovered area.\nLet's assume there are two windows on each wall, so we'll need to subtract 2 sq ft per window to account for them.\n\nStep 3: Calculate the remaining uncovered area.\nUncovered area = Total area - Windows covered\n\nNow let's do the math:\n\nStep 1:\n\\(10 \\times 8 = 80\\) sq ft\n\\(10 \\times 8 = 80\\) sq ft\n\\(5 \\times 8 = 40\\) sq ft\n\\(5 \\times 8 = 40\\) sq ft\n\nTotal area = 80 + 80 + 40 + 40 = 240 sq ft\n\nStep 2:\n(80 + 40) - (2 * 2)\n= 120 - 4\n= 116 sq ft\n\nStep 3:\n116 sq ft - 2 sq ft (windows covered) = 114 sq ft uncovered\n\nTherefore, the cost would be \\(114 \\text{ sq ft} / 20 \\text{ sq ft/gallon} = 5.70 \\text{ gallons}\\). \n\nCost": 1, "First, let's calculate the total area of the rooms:\n\nNorth and south walls: \\(10 \\text{ ft} \\times 8 \\text{ ft} = 80 \\text{ sq ft}\\)\nEast and west walls: \\(5 \\text{ ft} \\times 8 \\text{ ft} = 40 \\text{ sq ft}\\)\n\nTotal area of both walls: \\(80 \\text{ sq ft} + 40 \\text{ sq ft} = 120 \\text{ sq ft}\\)\n\nNow, we need to determine how many gallons of paint are required:\n\n\\(120 \\text{ sq ft} \\div 20 \\text{ sq ft/gallon} = 6 \\text{ gallons}\\)\n\nEach gallon covers 20 sq ft, so the total coverage needed is:\n\n\\(6 \\text{ gallons} \\times 20 \\text{ sq ft/gallon} = 120 \\text{ sq ft}\\)\n\nSince the paint costs $12 per gallon, the total cost would be:\n\n\\(120 \\text{ sq ft} \\times \\$12/\\text{sq ft} = \\$\\boxed{1440}\\).": 1, 'To calculate how much it will cost to paint the room, we first need to find the total area of all four walls. \n\nThe area of one wall is calculated by multiplying its length by its width:\n\nNorth and South Walls: \\( 10 \\text{ ft} \\times 8 \\text{ ft} = 80 \\text{ sq ft} \\)\nEast and West Walls: \\( 5 \\text{ ft} \\times 8 \\text{ ft} = 40 \\text{ sq ft} \\)\n\nTotal Wall Area: \\( 80 \\text{ sq ft} + 40 \\text{ sq ft} = 120 \\text{ sq ft} \\)\n\nNow, since a gallon of paint can cover 20 square feet, we divide the total wall area by the coverage capacity to get the number of gallons needed:\n\n\\( \\frac{120 \\text{ sq ft}}{20 \\text{ sq ft/gallon}} = 6 \\text{ gallons} \\)\n\nGiven each gallon costs $12, we multiply the number of gallons needed by the price per gallon to find the total cost:\n\n\\( 6 \\text{ gallons} \\times \\$12/\\text{gallon} = \\$72 \\)\n\nSo, it will cost $72 to paint the room.': 1, '48': 1, '72': 1}
