lculate Jeff's age based on his relationship with Martha.\nJeff is 10 years older than Martha.\nSo, Jeff's age = 20 + 10 = 30 years old.\n\nTherefore, Jeff is 30 years old.": 1, 'To find out how old Jeff is, we can break down the information given:\n\n1. Martha is 4 years younger than Mike, so Martha is 24 - 4 = 20 years old.\n2. Jeff is 10 years older than Martha, so Jeff is 20 + 10 = 30 years old.\n\nTherefore, Jeff is 30 years old.': 1, "To find out how old Jeff is, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. We know Mike is 24 years old.\n2. Martha is 4 years younger than Mike, so Martha's age would be:\n   24 - 4 = 20 years old.\n3. Jeff is 10 years older than Martha, so Jeff's age would be:\n   20 + 10 = 30 years old.\n\nTherefore, Jeff is 30 years old.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1103
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 1/5 answer='106'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 2/5 answer="First, we determine how many jellyfish are large. Since one-fifth of the jellyfish are large, the number of large jellyfish is 100 / 5 = 20.\nNext, we know that out of these large jellyfish, 1/3 change color when UV light is turned on, so the number of colored large jellyfish is 20 * (1/3) = 20/3 ≈ 6.67. Since we can't have a fraction of a jellyfish, we round down to 6 since we cannot have fractional jellyfish.\nFinally, we have 6 colored large jellyfish + 20 non-colored large jellyfish = 26 large jellyfish.\nFor the remaining 1/3 of the jellyfish (20), all of them remain blue regardless of the UV light condition.\nTherefore, there are a total of 26 + 20 = 46 jellyfish in the tank."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 3/5 answer='There are 6/x jellyfish because there are 6 total changes, and 5 are large and need to change back to green, so one-third of them (6/3) will have changed color. There are also 5 large jellyfish, so they will all change back to green. This means that 6/3 + 5 = 7 jellyfish will change color.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's determine how many large jellyfish there are:\n\nGiven that one-fifth of the jellyfish are large:\nTotal number of jellyfish = 1 (total) / 5 (large fraction)\nTotal number of jellyfish = 1 / 5\n\nNow we know that out of these, 1 out of every 3 changes color from green to blue under UV light. Since 6 jellyfish were observed to change color when UV light was turned on:\n\nFraction changing color = 6 / 1 (since we're dealing with whole numbers)\n\nSo the number of jellyfish that change color is given by:\n\nNumber of jellyfish changing color = Fraction changing color * Total number of jellyfish\n6 = 6 / 1 * 1 / 5\n6 = 6 / 5\n\nTherefore, the total number of jellyfish in the tank is 5."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 5/5 answer='54'
