on food would be:\n$30/fish * 3 fish = $90\n\nSo Jen spends $90 on food in the month of May.': 1, '432': 1, 'To find out how much Jen spends on fish food in the month of May, we first need to calculate the total cost for one fish. Since each fish needs $1 worth of food, the cost for one fish is $1.\n\nNext, we multiply the cost per fish by the number of days in May (approximately 30 days). This gives us:\n\n$1/day × 30 days = $30\n\nSo, Jen spends $30 on fish food in the month of May.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1161
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 1/5 answer="First, we calculate the total amount of land Abraham sold:\nHalf of the land sold for $50 each = $50 * (1/2) = $25\n\nAnother quarter of the land sold for $30 each = $30 * (1/4) = $7.50\n\nNow, let's calculate the revenue from these sales:\nRevenue from first sale = $25\nRevenue from second sale = $7.50\nTotal revenue from sales = $25 + $7.50 = $32.50\n\nNext, we subtract the cost of the land from the total revenue to find out how much money Abraham can make from selling the entire land:\nLand cost = $80\nRevenue from sales = $32.50\nMoney left to earn = $80 - $32.50 = $47.50\n\nAbraham sells the remaining land at $3 per square meter. First, we determine how many square meters remain:\nRemaining land = Total land - Land already sold = 80 - ($25 + $7.50) = 80 - $32.50 = 47.50\n\nFinally, we calculate the earnings from selling the remaining land:\nEarnings from remaining land = Remaining land * Price per square meter = 47.50 * $3 = $142.50\n\nAdding up the earnings from all sales gives us the total amount Abraham will have after selling all his unused land:\nTotal earnings = Money left to earn + Earnings from remaining land = $47.50 + $142.50 = $190\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $190 after selling all his unused land."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 2/5 answer="To calculate how much money Abraham can earn from selling all his unused land, we'll break down the transactions:\n\n1. Abraham initially owns 80 square meters.\n2. He sells half of it (40 sqm) for $50 each:\n   40sqm / 2 = 20 sqm\n   Earnings from first sale: 20sqm * $50/sqm = $1000\n3. After a month, he sells the other 40 sqm for $30 each:\n   40sqm / 4 = 10sqm\n   Earnings from second sale: 10sqm * $30/sqm = $300\n4. He sells the remaining 40 sqm for $3 per sqm:\n   40sqm / 4 = 10sqm\n   Earnings from third sale: 10sqm * $3/sqm = $30\n\nNow let's add up all these earnings:\n$1000 + $300 + $30 = $1330\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $1330 after selling all his unused land."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 3/5 answer='450'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 4/5 answer="First, let's calculate how much land Abraham bought:\nHe sold half (80 / 2) for $50, so he bought 80 / 2 = 40 square meters.\n\nThen we'll find out how much land he sold again:\nHe sold 1/4 (80 / 4) for $30, so he bought 80 / 4 = 20 square meters.\n\nNow we can calculate how much land he still has left:\nTotal land: 80 square meters.\nLand sold before (half): 80 / 2 = 40 square meters.\nLand sold after (1/4): 20 square meters.\n\nFinally, we'll sum up all the sales:\n$50 from first sale + $30 from second sale + $3 per square meter for the remaining land.\nSo, total earnings: $50 + $30 + ($30 x 20).\n\nLet's do the math:\n\n$50 (first sale)\n+$30 (second sale) = $80\n\nFor the remaining 20 square meters at $3 per square meter:\n$3 x 20 = $60\n\nAdding these together: $80 + $60 = $140\n\nTherefore, Abraham will be able to earn $140 after selling all his unused land."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 87/100 path 5/5 answer="To calculate how much money Abraham can earn from selling his unused land, we'll break down the transactions into steps:\n\n1. **First Transaction**: Abraham sold half of his 80 square meters of land for $50 each. So:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Amount from first transaction} = \\frac{80}{2} \\times 50 = 40 \\times 50 = \\$2000\n   \\]\n\n2. **Second Transaction**: After the first sale, Abraham sold another 1/4 of his land for $30 each. Since he had already sold half, the second sale was with the full amount he initially received:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Amount from second transaction} = 40 \\times 30 = \\$1200\n   \\]\n\n3. **Third Transaction**: Finally, Abraham sold the remaining 1/4 of his land at $3 per square meter. First, we need to find out how much land he actually has left:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Remaining land} = 80 - \\frac{80}{4} = 80 - 20 = 60 \\text{ square meters}\n   \\]\n   Now, selling these 60 square meters for $3 per square meter:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Total earnings from third transaction} = 60 \\times 3 = \\$180\n   \\]\n\nNow, we sum up the earnings from all three transactions:\n\\[\n\\text{Total earnings} = \\$2000 + \\$1200 + \\$180 = \\$3380\n\\]\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $3380 after selling all his unused land."
