at $3 per square meter. First, we determine how many square meters remain:\nRemaining land = Total land - Land already sold = 80 - ($25 + $7.50) = 80 - $32.50 = 47.50\n\nFinally, we calculate the earnings from selling the remaining land:\nEarnings from remaining land = Remaining land * Price per square meter = 47.50 * $3 = $142.50\n\nAdding up the earnings from all sales gives us the total amount Abraham will have after selling all his unused land:\nTotal earnings = Money left to earn + Earnings from remaining land = $47.50 + $142.50 = $190\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $190 after selling all his unused land.": 1, "To calculate how much money Abraham can earn from selling all his unused land, we'll break down the transactions:\n\n1. Abraham initially owns 80 square meters.\n2. He sells half of it (40 sqm) for $50 each:\n   40sqm / 2 = 20 sqm\n   Earnings from first sale: 20sqm * $50/sqm = $1000\n3. After a month, he sells the other 40 sqm for $30 each:\n   40sqm / 4 = 10sqm\n   Earnings from second sale: 10sqm * $30/sqm = $300\n4. He sells the remaining 40 sqm for $3 per sqm:\n   40sqm / 4 = 10sqm\n   Earnings from third sale: 10sqm * $3/sqm = $30\n\nNow let's add up all these earnings:\n$1000 + $300 + $30 = $1330\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $1330 after selling all his unused land.": 1, '450': 1, "First, let's calculate how much land Abraham bought:\nHe sold half (80 / 2) for $50, so he bought 80 / 2 = 40 square meters.\n\nThen we'll find out how much land he sold again:\nHe sold 1/4 (80 / 4) for $30, so he bought 80 / 4 = 20 square meters.\n\nNow we can calculate how much land he still has left:\nTotal land: 80 square meters.\nLand sold before (half): 80 / 2 = 40 square meters.\nLand sold after (1/4): 20 square meters.\n\nFinally, we'll sum up all the sales:\n$50 from first sale + $30 from second sale + $3 per square meter for the remaining land.\nSo, total earnings: $50 + $30 + ($30 x 20).\n\nLet's do the math:\n\n$50 (first sale)\n+$30 (second sale) = $80\n\nFor the remaining 20 square meters at $3 per square meter:\n$3 x 20 = $60\n\nAdding these together: $80 + $60 = $140\n\nTherefore, Abraham will be able to earn $140 after selling all his unused land.": 1, "To calculate how much money Abraham can earn from selling his unused land, we'll break down the transactions into steps:\n\n1. **First Transaction**: Abraham sold half of his 80 square meters of land for $50 each. So:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Amount from first transaction} = \\frac{80}{2} \\times 50 = 40 \\times 50 = \\$2000\n   \\]\n\n2. **Second Transaction**: After the first sale, Abraham sold another 1/4 of his land for $30 each. Since he had already sold half, the second sale was with the full amount he initially received:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Amount from second transaction} = 40 \\times 30 = \\$1200\n   \\]\n\n3. **Third Transaction**: Finally, Abraham sold the remaining 1/4 of his land at $3 per square meter. First, we need to find out how much land he actually has left:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Remaining land} = 80 - \\frac{80}{4} = 80 - 20 = 60 \\text{ square meters}\n   \\]\n   Now, selling these 60 square meters for $3 per square meter:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Total earnings from third transaction} = 60 \\times 3 = \\$180\n   \\]\n\nNow, we sum up the earnings from all three transactions:\n\\[\n\\text{Total earnings} = \\$2000 + \\$1200 + \\$180 = \\$3380\n\\]\n\nSo, Abraham will be able to earn $3380 after selling all his unused land.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1182
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 1/5 answer="First, we find out how much each school gets based on their total contribution. Since the total amount spent is $27000 and it's split evenly among 3 schools, each school receives $27000 / 3 = $9000. \n\nNext, we know that they can buy 100 books for $500. This means each book costs them $500 / 100 = $5.\n\nTo find out how many books each school can buy per school, we divide the cost of one book by the number of books each school can purchase with the funds available from their total contribution. So, each school can buy $5 / 9000 / (100 - 5) books.\n\nLet's calculate this:\nEach school buys 9000 / (100 - 5) books. \n9000 / 99 ≈ 90.91 books.\n\nSo, each school can buy approximately 91 books per school. However, since we're dealing with whole books, we'll round down to the nearest whole number because you can't buy a fraction of a book.\n\nThus, each school can buy 90 books per school."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 2/5 answer='First, we calculate how many books Bob can buy with his initial budget of $27,000, given that each book costs $500. This can be done by dividing the total amount by the cost per book: $27,000 / $500 = 54 books. Since Bob wants to distribute these 54 books among three schools, we divide the number of books by the number of schools: 54 / 3 = 18 books per school. Therefore, Bob can buy 18 books per school.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 3/5 answer="First, let's calculate how much money Bob has left after buying the books:\n\nBob spent $27,000 and can buy 100 books with his remaining $5,000 (since 27,000 - 100 \\times 500 = 27,000).\n\nNow we know that Bob spends $5,000 on 100 books. To find out how much money each book costs, we divide the total amount spent on books by the number of books:\n\n$5,000 / 100 books = $50/book\n\nSo each book costs $50. Now, if Bob wants to buy all 3 schools, we divide the cost of one school by the number of schools:\n\n$50/book × 3 schools = $150\n\nTherefore, Bob can buy 150 books per school."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 4/5 answer='To find out how many books each school can buy, first calculate the total amount spent on books. Given that Bob spends $27000 in total and he can purchase 100 books for $500, the total cost for 100 books is:\n\nTotal cost for 100 books = $500\n\nNow, divide the total amount Bob spends by the number of books he can buy to find out how many books one school can afford:\n\nNumber of books per school = Total cost for 100 books / Cost per book\n                           = $500 / $500\n                           = 1\n\nTherefore, Bob can buy 1 book per school.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 5/5 answer='To find out how many books each school can buy with their remaining budget, first calculate the total amount spent on books so far:\nBob has already spent $27000 - $500 (for 100 books) = $26500 on books.\n\nSince he wants to distribute this evenly among 3 schools, we divide the remaining budget by the number of schools:\n$26500 ÷ 3 = $8833.33... \n\nTherefore, each school can buy approximately $8833.33 worth of books.'
