l budget of $27,000, given that each book costs $500. This can be done by dividing the total amount by the cost per book: $27,000 / $500 = 54 books. Since Bob wants to distribute these 54 books among three schools, we divide the number of books by the number of schools: 54 / 3 = 18 books per school. Therefore, Bob can buy 18 books per school.': 1, "First, let's calculate how much money Bob has left after buying the books:\n\nBob spent $27,000 and can buy 100 books with his remaining $5,000 (since 27,000 - 100 \\times 500 = 27,000).\n\nNow we know that Bob spends $5,000 on 100 books. To find out how much money each book costs, we divide the total amount spent on books by the number of books:\n\n$5,000 / 100 books = $50/book\n\nSo each book costs $50. Now, if Bob wants to buy all 3 schools, we divide the cost of one school by the number of schools:\n\n$50/book × 3 schools = $150\n\nTherefore, Bob can buy 150 books per school.": 1, 'To find out how many books each school can buy, first calculate the total amount spent on books. Given that Bob spends $27000 in total and he can purchase 100 books for $500, the total cost for 100 books is:\n\nTotal cost for 100 books = $500\n\nNow, divide the total amount Bob spends by the number of books he can buy to find out how many books one school can afford:\n\nNumber of books per school = Total cost for 100 books / Cost per book\n                           = $500 / $500\n                           = 1\n\nTherefore, Bob can buy 1 book per school.': 1, 'To find out how many books each school can buy with their remaining budget, first calculate the total amount spent on books so far:\nBob has already spent $27000 - $500 (for 100 books) = $26500 on books.\n\nSince he wants to distribute this evenly among 3 schools, we divide the remaining budget by the number of schools:\n$26500 ÷ 3 = $8833.33... \n\nTherefore, each school can buy approximately $8833.33 worth of books.': 1}
