[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 1/5 answer="First, let's calculate how many days Josh works each week:\n- Monday through Friday: 5 days (including holidays)\n- Saturday and Sunday: 2 days\nTotal working days each week: 5 + 2 = <<5+2=7>>\n\nNext, we'll determine how many cars he can service in one week:\n- He works 3 days a week but takes Sundays off, so he only works 7 - 2 = <<7-2=5>>5 days a week.\n- Since he services 3 cars per day, he can service 3 cars/day * 5 days/week = <<3*5=15>>15 cars/week.\n\nNow, let's find out his weekly earnings:\n- He makes $4 per car.\n- So, $4/car * 15 cars/week = <<$4*cars*15=$60*cars/week>>\n\nFinally, let's calculate his total earnings over 2 weeks:\n- Weekly earnings: $60/cars/week = <<$60*cars/week>>\n- 2 weeks: <<$60*cars/week*2=<<2*60=cars*2>>2*120=<<2*120=240>>240\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $240 in 2 weeks."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 2/5 answer='First, we calculate how many days the car service cycle occurs:\n- Regular days: Monday through Friday (5 days)\n- Sundays: 0 days\n\nTotal days in a week: 5 + 1 = 6 days\n\nSince there are 2 weeks, we multiply the total number of days by the number of weeks:\n\n6 days/week * 2 weeks = 12 days\n\nNow, we calculate his earnings from one cycle:\n- Number of cars serviced per cycle: 3 cars/day\n- Total cycles in a week: 6 days\n- Total cycles in a 2-week period: 6 days * 2 weeks = 12 cycles\n\nEarnings per cycle: 3 cars/cycle * $4/car = $<<3*4=12>>12\n\nFinally, we calculate his weekly earnings:\n- Earnings per cycle: $12\n- Cycles in a week: 12 cycles\n- Weekly earnings: $12 * 12 = $<<12*12=144>>144\n\nJosh makes $144 in 2 weeks.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 3/5 answer="Josh works 7 days a week, but on Sundays and Wednesdays, he doesn't work. That leaves him working 5 regular days a week (Monday through Thursday).\n\nHe services 3 cars each day, so he services 5 cars x 3 cars/day = 15 cars a week.\n\nHe makes $4 per car, so he makes 15 cars/week x $4/car = $<<15*4=60>>60 per week.\n\nIn 2 weeks, he would make $60/car x 15 cars/week = $<<60*15=900>>900 per week.\n\nSince there are 14 days in a week (assuming it's Monday through Friday), he would make $900/car x 14 cars/week = $<<900*14=12600>>12600 per week.\n\nTo find out how much he makes in 2 weeks, we multiply his weekly earnings by 2:\n\n$12600/week x 2 weeks = $<<12600*2=25200>>25200.\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $25,200 over 2 weeks at his car service job."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 4/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 4/5 answer='First, calculate how many days there are in 2 weeks:\n2 weeks × 7 days/week = <<2*7=14>>14 days\n\nNext, subtract the number of holidays (Sunday and Wednesday) from the total days in 2 weeks:\n14 days - 2 days = <<14-2=12>>12 days\n\nNow, calculate how many hours Josh works each day:\n3 cars/day × 8 hours/car = <<3*8=24>>24 hours/day\n\nFinally, calculate his weekly earnings:\n24 hours/day × 12 days/week = <<24*12=288>>288 dollars/week\n\nTo find out his total earnings over 2 weeks, multiply his weekly earnings by the number of weeks:\n288 dollars/week × 2 weeks = <<288*2=576>>576 dollars\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $576 in 2 weeks.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 5/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 5/5 answer="To calculate Josh's total earnings over 2 weeks, we'll first determine his daily earnings from service each day of the week (except Sundays and Wednesdays), and then multiply by 5 days (since he works every day but doesn't work on Sunday or Wednesday).\n\nOn weekdays:\n- He services 3 cars per day.\n- His weekly earnings from weekdays would be \\(3 \\text{ cars/day} \\times 5 \\text{ days/week} = 15 \\text{ dollars/week}\\).\n\nOn weekends:\n- He services 3 cars per day (Saturday and Sunday).\n- There are 2 weekend days in 5 weekdays, so he would have \\(3 \\text{ cars/day} \\times 2 \\text{ days} = 6 \\text{ cars/weekend}\\) minus \\(2 \\text{ cars/weekend} \\times \\$4/\\text{car} = \\$6\\). This leaves him with \\(6 \\text{ cars/weekend} \\times \\$4/\\text{car} = \\$24\\).\n\nNow we can find the total earnings for 2 weeks:\n- Weekday earnings: \\(15 \\text{ dollars/week}\\)\n- Weekend earnings: \\$24\n\nTotal earnings in 2 weeks: \\(15 + 24 = \\$39\\).\n\nTherefore, Josh makes \\$39 in 2 weeks. The final answer is 39."
