[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 1/5 answer='First, we determine how far Aaron runs in one mile:\nAaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, so he runs each mile at \\(\\frac{1}{2}\\) of what Vanessa can do. This means Aaron runs 1 mile in \\(\\frac{1}{2} \\times 16\\) minutes. So, it takes him \\(16 \\div \\frac{1}{2} = 16 \\times 2 = 32\\) minutes to run one mile.\n\nVanessa runs 4 miles, so the total time she takes is \\(4 \\times 16\\) minutes. Therefore, it takes Vanessa \\(4 \\times 16 = 64\\) minutes to complete her part of the race.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/5 answer='First, we find out how long it takes for Aaron to complete his part of the race. Since Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, and Vanessa runs 4 miles in 16 minutes, it will take Aaron 4 miles x (2 * 16 minutes) = 96 minutes to finish one mile.\n\nVanessa can run 4 miles in 16 minutes, so the time it takes for Vanessa to run all four miles is 16 minutes x 4 = 64 minutes.\n\nTherefore, Vanessa took 64 minutes to complete her part of the race.'
