[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 100/100 path 2/5 answer="First, let's calculate the discount on the radiator:\nDiscounted price: $400 x (1 - 0.80) = $400 x 0.20 = $<<400*0.20=80>>80\n\nNext, we'll calculate the total cost for the installation:\nCost for hiring the mechanic: $50/hour x 3 hours = $<<50*3=150>>150\n\nFinally, we'll sum up all the costs:\nTotal cost: Discount + Installation cost = $80 + $150 = $<<80+150=230>>230\n\nTherefore, Mark paid $230 in total."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 100/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 100/100 path 3/5 answer='First, we calculate the discounted price of the new radiator:\nDiscounted price = Original price - Discount amount\n                 = $400 - ($400 * 80%)\n                 = $400 - $320\n                 = $80\n\nThen, we calculate the total cost for hiring a mechanic:\nTotal cost for mechanic installation = Time * Rate per hour\n                                   = 3 * $50\n                                   = $150\n\nFinally, we add up all the costs:\nTotal cost = Cost of radiator + Total time spent installing\n           = $80 + $150\n           = $230\n\nTherefore, Mark paid a total of $230 for getting his car fixed.'
