[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 1/3 answer="Let's break it down step-by-step:\n\n1. Melanie started with 5 vacuum cleaners.\n2. She sold a third of them at the green house:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{3} \\times 5 = \\frac{5}{3} \\approx 1.67\n   \\]\n   Since we can't have a fraction of a vacuum cleaner, let's assume she sold 1 vacuum cleaner (rounding up because you can't sell a fraction).\n   \n3. She sold 2 more to the red house:\n   \\[\n   1 + 2 = 3\n   \\]\n\n4. After selling to the red house, she had:\n   \\[\n   5 - 3 = 2\n   \\]\n   vacuum cleaners left.\n\n5. She then sold half of what was left at the orange house:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{2} \\times 2 = 1\n   \\]\n\nSo, Melanie started with 5 vacuum cleaners, but now she has 1 vacuum cleaner left. This means she must have started with:\n\\[\n5 + 1 = 6\n\\]\n\nTherefore, Melanie started with 6 vacuum cleaners."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 2/3 answer="Let's break down the problem step-by-step:\n\n1. Melanie started with \\( V \\) vacuum cleaners.\n2. She sold a third of them at the green house:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{V}{3}\n   \\]\n3. She sold 2 more vacuum cleaners at the red house:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{V}{3} + 2\n   \\]\n4. At the orange house, she sold half of what was left from the total:\n   \\[\n   \\left(\\frac{V}{3}\\right) + 2 - \\left(\\frac{V}{3} + 2\\right)/2 = \\frac{V}{3} + 2 - \\frac{V}{6} - 1 = \\frac{V}{6}\n   \\]\n\nAfter all these transactions, she had 5 vacuum cleaners left:\n\\[\n\\frac{V}{6} = 5\n\\]\n\nTo find out how many vacuum cleaners she originally had, we solve for \\( V \\):\n\\[\nV = 5 \\times 6 = 30\n\\]\n\nTherefore, Melanie started with 30 vacuum cleaners."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 3/3 answer="Let's break down the problem step by step:\n\n1. Melanie started with \\( V \\) vacuum cleaners.\n2. At the first stage, she sold a third of her vacuum cleaners:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{V}{3}\n   \\]\n3. After selling at the first stage, she had:\n   \\[\n   V - \\frac{V}{3} = \\frac{2V}{3}\n   \\]\n\n4. At the second stage, she sold 2 more vacuum cleaners:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{2V}{3} + 2\n   \\]\n\n5. After selling at the second stage, she had:\n   \\[\n   \\left( \\frac{2V}{3} + 2 \\right) - \\left( \\frac{2V}{3} \\right) = 2\n   \\]\n\n6. According to the problem, after these two stages, she still had 5 vacuum cleaners left:\n   \\[\n   2 - 5 = -3\n   \\]\n\nSince the number of vacuum cleaners cannot be negative, it seems there might be a mistake or misunderstanding in the initial setup. Let's re-evaluate the steps carefully:\n\nGiven:\n- Total vacuum cleaners sold so far: \\(\\frac{2V}{3}\\)\n- Vacuum cleaners left: 5\n\nWe can set up the equation based on the information given:\n\\[\n\\frac{2V}{3} + 2 = 5\n\\]\n\nSolving for \\( V \\):\n\\[\n\\frac{2V}{3} = 5 - 2\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{2V}{3} = 3\n\\]\n\\[\n2V = 9\n\\]\n\\[\nV = \\frac{9}{2}\n\\]\n\\[\nV = 4.5\n\\]\n\nTherefore"
