[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 start id=gsm8k_test_51
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's calculate how far Tom travels during his journey from 1 to 4 PM:\n\n- From 1 AM to 4 AM (4 hours) - 10 mph * 4 hours = 40 miles\n\nNow, he travels back at 6 mph for the remaining time:\n\n- Time taken to return = 4 hours - 4 hours = 0 hours (since he already traveled 40 miles)\n\nSo, it takes him 0 hours to return since he didn't travel back yet when we started our calculation."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 2/3 answer='First, we calculate how far Tom travels during his journey from 1 to 4 PM:\n\n- From 1 AM to 4 AM, he sails at 10 mph. So, in one hour, he covers 10 miles.\n- Therefore, in two hours (from 1 AM to 4 AM), he will have traveled 2 * 10 = 20 miles.\n\nNow, we consider the return trip:\n- From 4 AM to 12 AM, he sails at 6 mph.\n- In one hour, he covers 6 miles.\n- Therefore, in two hours (from 4 AM to 12 AM), he will have traveled 2 * 6 = 12 miles.\n\nTo find out how long it takes him to complete both trips, we add the distances together:\n- Total distance = 20 miles + 12 miles = 32 miles\n\nSince he travels at 10 mph for each leg of the trip, we divide the total distance by the speed to find the time taken:\n- Time = 32 miles / 10 mph = 3.2 hours\n\nTherefore, it takes Tom 3.2 hours to complete both trips.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 2/100 path 3/3 answer='First, we calculate the time it takes for Tom to sail from 1 to 4 PM. Since he sails at a speed of 10 miles per hour, the time taken is 4 hours (from 1 PM to 4 PM).\n\nNext, we calculate the distance he covers during his trip from 1 to 4 PM. Since he sails at a speed of 10 miles per hour, the distance covered is 10 miles/hour * 4 hours = 40 miles.\n\nNow, we consider the return trip. He travels at a speed of 6 mph, so the time taken for the return trip is 40 miles / 6 mph = approximately 6.67 hours.\n\nTo find out how long it takes him to get back, we add the time for the trip from 1 to 4 PM to the time for the return trip:\n\n4 hours + 6.67 hours = 10.67 hours\n\nTherefore, it takes Tom approximately 10.67 hours to get back.'
