[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 start id=gsm8k_test_65
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 1/3 answer='First, we calculate how long Jim spends reading each time he goes to bed and reads. Since he reads for half as long as he watches TV, he reads for 2 hours / 2 = 1 hour each time. \n\nNext, we multiply his weekly reading time by the number of times he reads in a week:\n\n1 hour/reading session × 3 sessions/week = 3 hours/week\n\nFinally, we multiply the total weekly reading time by the number of weeks (which is given as 4):\n\n3 hours/week × 4 weeks = 12 hours\n\nSo, Jim spends 12 hours on TV and reading in 4 weeks.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 2/3 answer='First, we calculate how long Jim spends reading each time he goes to bed and reads. Since he reads for half as long as he watches TV, and he spends 2 hours watching TV, he reads for 2 / 2 = 1 hour. \n\nNext, we calculate how many hours he spends reading over 3 days:\n1 hour/day * 3 days/week = 3 hours/week\n\nFinally, we multiply the weekly reading hours by the number of weeks (4):\n3 hours/week * 4 weeks = 12 hours\n\nSo, Jim spends 12 hours on TV and reading in 4 weeks.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 5/100 path 3/3 answer='First, we calculate how long Jim reads each time. Since he reads half as long as he watches TV, and he spends 2 hours watching TV, he reads 2 / 2 = 1 hour each time.\n\nNext, we multiply the number of times he reads (3 times) by the duration he spends reading each time (1 hour). So, 3 * 1 = 3 hours.\n\nFinally, we add the hours spent watching TV (2 hours) and the hours spent reading (3 hours) together. Thus, 2 + 3 = 5 hours.\n\nTherefore, Jim spends 5 hours on TV and reading in 4 weeks.'
