[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 8/100 path 1/3 answer="First, we determine how many photographs Jamal's phone can hold. Since it holds 6 times more photographs than Brittany's phone, we divide the number of photographs Jamal's phone can hold by 6:\nNumber of photographs in Brittany's phone = 1800 / 6 = 300 photographs\n\nNext, we know that Brittany's phone can hold up to 50 times more photographs than the number of birds in her photo of the ducks at the zoo. So, we multiply the number of photographs in Brittany's phone by 50 to find out how many ducks she could see:\nNumber of photographs in Brittany's phone (for ducks) = 300 * 50 = 15000 photographs\n\nTherefore, Jamal's photograph of ducks at the zoo can show 15000 photographs, or approximately 15,000 ducks."
