[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 start id=gsm8k_test_135
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 1/3 answer="First, we calculate the number of video games Brian's friend Bobby has. Since Brian initially had 20 video games and lost 5 right before the comparison, he now has \\(20 - 5 = 15\\) video games. \n\nBobby has 5 fewer than 3 times as many video games as Brian. So, Bobby has \\(3 \\times 15 - 5\\) video games. Let's do the math:\n\n\\(3 \\times 15 - 5 = 45 - 5 = 40\\)\n\nTherefore, Bobby has 40 video games."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 2/3 answer='First, we determine how many video games Brian had before losing some. Since he originally had 20 video games and lost 5, he now has \\(20 - 5 = 15\\) video games. \n\nBobby has 5 fewer than 3 times as many video games as Brian. So, if Brian has 15 video games, Bobby has \\(3 \\times 15 - 5 = 45 - 5 = 40\\) video games.\n\nTherefore, Bobby has 40 video games.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 9/100 path 3/3 answer="First, let's find out how many video games Brian's friend Bobby has initially. Since he has 5 fewer than 3 times as many as Brian, we can calculate it like this:\n\nBrian's video games + 5 = Bobby's video games\n\nGiven that Brian has 20 video games, we can set up the equation:\n\n20 + 5 = Bobby's video games\n\nBobby has 25 video games.\n\nNow, since Brian lost 5 video games before the comparison was made, we subtract those from his total:\n\n25 (Bobby's total) - 5 (lost) = 20 video games left for Bobby.\n\nSo, Bobby has 20 video games."
