[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 start id=gsm8k_test_206
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 1/3 answer="To calculate the total distance Michael rode his bike, we'll break down the problem into two parts:\n\n1. For the first 4 weeks:\n   - He rides the bike 5 days a week (Monday through Friday), so he rides 5 days/week * 4 weeks = 20 days.\n   - Each day he rides 25 km, so over 20 days he rides 20 days * 25 km/day = 500 km.\n\n2. For the next 3 weeks:\n   - He now rides the bike 2 days a week (Saturday and Sunday), so he rides 2 days/week * 3 weeks = 6 days.\n   - Each day he rides 60 km, so over 6 days he rides 6 days * 60 km/day = 360 km.\n\nNow, we add up both parts to get the total distance:\nTotal distance = Distance from first period + Distance from second period\nTotal distance = 500 km + 360 km = 860 km\n\nTherefore, Michael rode his bike for a total of 860 kilometers."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 18/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many kilometers Michael rode in the first two weeks:\n\nFor the first two weeks:\n- He rode the bike 5 times a week, so he rode \\(5 \\times 25\\) kilometers each time.\n- This totals \\(5 \\times 25 = 125\\) kilometers over those two weeks.\n\nNow, let's calculate how many kilometers he rode in the third week:\n\nFor the third week:\n- He decided to ride the bike only 2 times a week, so he rode \\(2 \\times 60\\) kilometers each time.\n- This totals \\(2 \\times 60 = 120\\) kilometers over those three weeks.\n\nTo find out the total number of kilometers Michael rode, we add the kilometers from both periods:\n\nTotal kilometers = (Kilometers from first two weeks) + (Kilometers from third week)\nTotal kilometers = 125 + 120\nTotal kilometers = 245\n\nTherefore, Michael rode a total of 245 kilometers in all."
