[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 start id=gsm8k_test_440
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 1/3 answer="First, we calculate the width of the room using its area and length:\n\\[ \\text{Width} = \\frac{\\text{Area}}{\\text{Length}} = \\frac{360}{3} = 120 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nTo find the perimeter, we use the formula for the perimeter of a rectangle:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (\\text{Length} + \\text{Width}) \\]\nSubstituting the values we have:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (3 + 120) = 2 \\times 123 = 246 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nSo, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 246 feet."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 2/3 answer='To find the perimeter of the rectangle, we first need to determine its width. We know the area (A) and one side (l), so we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle:\n\n\\[ A = l \\times w \\]\n\nGiven:\n- Area \\( A = 360 \\) square feet\n- Length \\( l = 3 \\) yards\n\nFirst, convert the length from yards to feet since 1 yard = 3 feet:\n\n\\[ l = 3 \\text{ yards} \\times 3 \\text{ feet/yard} = 9 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nNow, solve for the width \\( w \\):\n\n\\[ 360 = 9 \\times w \\]\n\\[ w = \\frac{360}{9} \\]\n\\[ w = 40 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nThe perimeter \\( P \\) of a rectangle is given by:\n\n\\[ P = 2(l + w) \\]\n\nSubstitute the values of \\( l \\) and \\( w \\):\n\n\\[ P = 2(9 + 40) \\]\n\\[ P = 2(49) \\]\n\\[ P = 98 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nSo, the perimeter of the room is 98 feet.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 path 3/3 start
