[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 34/100 done id=gsm8k_test_440 prediction="First, we calculate the width of the room using its area and length:\n\\[ \\text{Width} = \\frac{\\text{Area}}{\\text{Length}} = \\frac{360}{3} = 120 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nTo find the perimeter, we use the formula for the perimeter of a rectangle:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (\\text{Length} + \\text{Width}) \\]\nSubstituting the values we have:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (3 + 120) = 2 \\times 123 = 246 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nSo, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 246 feet." gold='98' correct=False vote_counts={"First, we calculate the width of the room using its area and length:\n\\[ \\text{Width} = \\frac{\\text{Area}}{\\text{Length}} = \\frac{360}{3} = 120 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nTo find the perimeter, we use the formula for the perimeter of a rectangle:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (\\text{Length} + \\text{Width}) \\]\nSubstituting the values we have:\n\\[ \\text{Perimeter} = 2 \\times (3 + 120) = 2 \\times 123 = 246 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nSo, the perimeter of Billie's rectangular bedroom is 246 feet.": 1, 'To find the perimeter of the rectangle, we first need to determine its width. We know the area (A) and one side (l), so we can use the formula for the area of a rectangle:\n\n\\[ A = l \\times w \\]\n\nGiven:\n- Area \\( A = 360 \\) square feet\n- Length \\( l = 3 \\) yards\n\nFirst, convert the length from yards to feet since 1 yard = 3 feet:\n\n\\[ l = 3 \\text{ yards} \\times 3 \\text{ feet/yard} = 9 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nNow, solve for the width \\( w \\):\n\n\\[ 360 = 9 \\times w \\]\n\\[ w = \\frac{360}{9} \\]\n\\[ w = 40 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nThe perimeter \\( P \\) of a rectangle is given by:\n\n\\[ P = 2(l + w) \\]\n\nSubstitute the values of \\( l \\) and \\( w \\):\n\n\\[ P = 2(9 + 40) \\]\n\\[ P = 2(49) \\]\n\\[ P = 98 \\text{ feet} \\]\n\nSo, the perimeter of the room is 98 feet.': 1, '98': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 start id=gsm8k_test_447
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how many points Joey is winning by, we first calculate the difference between his initial score and the total points he scored:\n\nJoey's initial score: 214 points\nMarcy's current score: 225 points\n\nDifference: 225 - 214 = 11 points\n\nSo, Joey is now winning by 11 points."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 2/3 answer="To determine how many points Joey is winning by, we'll calculate the net change in his score from before his turn until now:\n\n1. Before his turn, Joey had 214 points.\n2. After scoring 26 points, he would have:\n   214 + 26 = 240 points.\n3. Marcy added 10 points to Joey's score:\n   240 + 10 = 250 points.\n4. Now, Joey has 250 points compared to Marcy's 225 points.\n\nTo find out by how many points Joey is winning:\n   250 - 225 = 25 points.\n\nJoey is winning by 25 points."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 35/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate Joey's score after he receives 26 points from Scrabble:\nJoey's score = Initial score + Points received\nJoey's score = 214 + 26 = 240\n\nNext, we calculate Marcy's score after she receives 10 points:\nMarcy's score = Initial score + Points received\nMarcy's score = 225 + 10 = 235\n\nTo find out by how many points Joey is winning, we subtract Marcy's score from Joey's score:\nDifference = Joey's score - Marcy's score\nDifference = 240 - 235 = 5\n\nTherefore, Joey is winning by 5 points."
