[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 start id=gsm8k_test_451
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 1/3 answer="To solve this problem, let's break it down into steps:\n\n1. **Calculate the original cost per balloon:** \n   - Total cost for 20 balloons: $900\n   - Number of balloons: 20\n\n   Therefore, the original cost per balloon is:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Original Cost per Balloon} = \\frac{\\$900}{20} = \\$45\n   \\]\n\n2. **Calculate the new cost per balloon with the price increase:**\n   - Price increase per balloon: $20\n   - New cost per balloon: Original cost + Price Increase\n   \\[\n   \\text{New Cost per Balloon} = \\$45 + \\$20 = \\$65\n   \\]\n\n3. **Calculate the total cost for 170 balloons at the new price:**\n   - Number of balloons: 170\n\n   Therefore, the total cost for 170 balloons at the new price is:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Total Cost for 170 Balloons} = 170 \\times \\$65 = \\$11,050\n   \\]\n\nSo, Bentley paid $11,050 to fill 170 balloons after the price increase."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 2/3 answer='To find out how much Bentley paid to fill 170 balloons after the price increase, we first calculate the original cost per balloon before the price increase. Since the total cost for 20 balloons was $900, the cost per balloon would have been $900 / 20 = $45.\n\nNext, we apply the price increase of $20 to each balloon. So, the new cost per balloon would be $45 + $20 = $65.\n\nFinally, to find out how much Bentley paid to fill 170 balloons at the new price, we multiply the new cost per balloon by the number of balloons: $65 * 170 = $11,050.\n\nTherefore, Bentley paid $11,050 to fill 170 balloons after the price increase.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 37/100 path 3/3 answer='To solve this problem, we first calculate the original cost per balloon before the price increase:\n\nTotal cost for 20 balloons at $900 = $900\n\nCost per balloon = Total cost / Number of balloons\n                    = $900 / 20\n                    = $45\n\nNow, with the price increase, the new cost per balloon becomes:\n\nNew cost per balloon = Original cost per balloon + Increase\n                     = $45 + $20\n                     = $65\n\nFinally, to find out how much Bentley paid to fill 170 balloons at the new price:\n\nCost for 170 balloons at $65 per balloon\n                  = 170 balloons * $65/balloon\n                  = $11,050\n\nSo, Bentley paid $11,050 to fill 170 balloons after the price increase.'
