[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 1/3 answer='First, calculate the total number of cupcakes Mary can decorate with all 6 jars:\n\nEach jar decorates 8 cupcakes, so 6 jars will decorate 6 * 8 = 48 cupcakes.\n\nMary wants to use up all of her sprinkles, so she needs to bake enough cupcakes to have at least 48 cupcakes.\n\nSince each pan holds 12 cupcakes, we divide the total number of cupcakes needed by the capacity of one pan:\n\n48 cupcakes ÷ 12 cupcakes/pan = 4 pans.\n\nTherefore, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 40/100 path 2/3 answer='First, we calculate the total number of cupcakes Mary can decorate with all her jars:\n\nEach jar can decorate 8 cupcakes, so with 6 jars:\n\\[ 6 \\text{ jars} \\times 8 \\text{ cupcakes/jar} = 48 \\text{ cupcakes} \\]\n\nMary wants to use up all of her sprinkles, so she needs to bake enough cupcakes to have at least 48 cupcakes. Since each pan holds 12 cupcakes, we divide the total needed by the capacity of one pan:\n\n\\[ \\frac{48 \\text{ cupcakes}}{12 \\text{ cupcakes/pan}} = 4 \\text{ pans} \\]\n\nTherefore, Mary should bake 4 pans worth of cupcakes.'
