[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 start id=gsm8k_test_476
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 1/3 answer='To find out how many books each child received, we first calculate the total number of books Sarah bought:\n\nTotal cost = $300\nCost per book = $15\n\nNumber of books = Total cost / Cost per book\nNumber of books = $300 / $15\nNumber of books = 20\n\nNow, since Sarah gave an equal number of books to her 4 kids, we divide the total number of books by the number of kids:\n\nBooks per kid = Number of books / Number of kids\nBooks per kid = 20 / 4\nBooks per kid = 5\n\nSo, each child received 5 books.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 2/3 answer='To find out how many books each child received, we first need to determine how many books Sarah bought. Since each book cost $15 and she spent $300, we can divide the total amount spent by the price per book:\n\n$300 ÷ $15 = 20 books\n\nNow, since Sarah gave an equal number of books to her 4 kids, we divide the total number of books by the number of children:\n\n20 books ÷ 4 children = 5 books per child\n\nSo, each child received 5 books.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 41/100 path 3/3 answer='To find out how many books each child received, we divide the total amount spent by the price of one book. So, $300 ÷ $15 = 20 books. Since there were 4 kids, we divide the total number of books by the number of children. Therefore, 20 ÷ 4 = 5 books per child.'
