[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 42/100 path 2/3 answer="First, we calculate how many skeins Mariah used. Since she used \\( \\frac{1}{4} \\) of a skein, we multiply 1 by 4:\n\n\\( 1 \\times \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{1}{4} \\)\n\nNext, we calculate how many skeins Mariah's grandma used. She used \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) of a skein, so we multiply 2 by 1:\n\n\\( 2 \\times \\frac{1}{2} = 1 \\)\n\nNow, we add the two amounts together to find out how many skeins were used in total:\n\n\\( \\frac{1}{4} + 1 = \\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{4}{4} = \\frac{5}{4} \\)\n\nFinally, we convert this fraction into yards since there are 364 yards in a skein:\n\n\\( \\frac{5}{4} \\times 364 = 5 \\times 91 = 455 \\)\n\nSo, Mariah and her grandma used 455 yards of yarn altogether."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 42/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 42/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how many yards of yarn Mariah and her grandma used altogether, we first need to calculate how much yarn each of them used individually and then sum these amounts.\n\nMariah used \\( \\frac{1}{4} \\) of a skein of yarn, and there are 364 yards in a skein. So, Mariah used:\n\\[ \\text{Yarn used by Mariah} = \\frac{1}{4} \\times 364 \\]\n\nHer grandma used \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) of a skein of yarn, so she also used:\n\\[ \\text{Yarn used by Grandma} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 364 \\]\n\nNow, let's calculate the total amount of yarn used by both of them:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = \\text{Yarn used by Mariah} + \\text{Yarn used by Grandma} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = \\left( \\frac{1}{4} \\times 364 \\right) + \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\times 364 \\right) \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = \\left( \\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{1}{2} \\right) \\times 364 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = \\left( \\frac{1}{4} + \\frac{2}{4} \\right) \\times 364 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = \\frac{3}{4} \\times 364 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} = 3 \\times 91 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Total Yarn used} ="
