[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 43/100 path 3/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many sticks Frederick can get from each type of wood:\n\nFor the 2 x 4 piece:\n200 sticks / 200 pieces = 1 stick per piece\n\nFor the 2 x 8 piece:\n400 sticks / 200 pieces = 2 sticks per piece\n\nNow we'll compare the cost of each type of wood with the number of sticks it provides:\n\nCost of 2 x 4 piece wood:\n$4 (per stick) * 1 stick/piece = $4 per piece\n\nCost of 2 x 8 piece wood:\n$6 (per stick) * 2 sticks/piece = $12 per piece\n\nSince the 2 x 4 piece wood provides more sticks at a lower cost ($4 vs. $12), Frederick should use the 2 x 4 piece of wood. With $24, he can buy:\n$24 / $4 per stick = 6 sticks\n\nWith 6 sticks from the 2 x 4 piece, he will have enough sticks to make:\n6 sticks / 2 sticks per piece = 3 sets of 200 sticks\n\nSo, Frederick can make 3 * 200 sticks = 600 sticks.\n\nTherefore, the most popsicle sticks he can make is 600 sticks, using the cheapest lumber available."
