ld make 18 more vlogs to reach her goal of making 72 vlogs per month.': 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 start id=gsm8k_test_541
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how much Elvis has to save each day in the second half of the month, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. First, calculate the total amount Elvis needs to save in April:\n   - Monthly savings goal: $1125\n   - Number of days in April: 30 (assuming it's not a leap year)\n   - Total savings needed: $1125\n\n2. Since he wants to save twice as much in the second half of the month compared to the first half, let's denote the daily savings in the first half of the month as \\(x\\). Then, in the second half, he will save \\(2x\\) per day.\n\n3. To meet his goal of saving $1125, we set up the equation:\n   \\[\n   2x \\times 30 + x \\times 30 = 1125\n   \\]\n   Simplifying this gives us:\n   \\[\n   60x + 30x = 1125\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   90x = 1125\n   \\]\n\n4. Solving for \\(x\\):\n   \\[\n   x = \\frac{1125}{90} = 13.75\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, Elvis has to save $13.75 per day in the second half of the month."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out how much Elvis has to save each day in the second half of the month, we can set up an equation based on his goal to save twice as much daily in the second half of the month as he saved in the first half.\n\nLet \\( x \\) represent the amount Elvis saves in the first half of the month (in dollars). Since there are two halves to the month, the total savings for the first half would be \\( 2x \\).\n\nIn the second half of the month, he plans to save twice as much daily as he does in the first half. Therefore, he will save \\( 2 \\times 2x = 4x \\) dollars in the second half.\n\nSince there are 30 days in April, the total amount he aims to save in the entire month is:\n\\[ 2x + 4x = 6x \\]\n\nWe know that Elvis's monthly saving target is $1125, so:\n\\[ 6x = 1125 \\]\n\nSolving for \\( x \\):\n\\[ x = \\frac{1125}{6} \\]\n\\[ x = 187.5 \\]\n\nSo, Elvis saves $187.50 in the first half of the month and $375.00 in the second half of the month (since \\( 2 \\times 187.5 = 375 \\)).\n\nTherefore, Elvis has to save $375.00 in the second half of the month."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how much Elvis needs to save each day in the second half of the month, we can set up an equation based on his monthly savings goal. Let's denote the amount he saves in the first half of the month as \\(x\\). Since he wants to save twice as much in the second half, he will save \\(2x\\) in the second half.\n\nGiven:\n- Total monthly savings goal: $1125\n- Amount saved in the first half: \\(x\\)\n- Amount saved in the second half: \\(2x\\)\n\nSince there are approximately 4 weeks in a month (assuming 4 weeks), the total number of days in the month is \\(4 \\times 7 = 28\\).\n\nWe know that the total savings over these 28 days should equal the monthly savings goal:\n\n\\[x + 2x = 1125\\]\n\nCombining like terms gives us:\n\n\\[3x = 1125\\]\n\nSolving for \\(x\\):\n\n\\[x = \\frac{1125}{3} = 375\\]\n\nSo, Elvis saves $375 in the first half of the month. To find out how much he needs to save each day in the second half, we multiply the amount saved in the first half by 2:\n\n\\[2x = 2 \\times 375 = 750\\]\n\nTherefore, Elvis needs to save $750 each day in the second half of the month."
