[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 2/3 answer="To determine how much James spends on candles, we first need to figure out how many packs of candles he buys. \n\nFirst, let's find out how old the second son is:\n- The first son is 12 years old.\n- The second son is 4 years younger than the first son, so he is \\(12 - 4 = 8\\) years old.\n\nNext, we calculate how many packs of candles they need:\n- Each pack contains 5 candles.\n- They need 5 packs (one for each son).\n\nNow, we can calculate the total cost:\n- Each pack costs $3.\n- Therefore, 5 packs will cost \\(5 \\times 3 = \\$\\)15.\n\nSo, James spends $15 on candles."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 50/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate the age difference between the two sons: 12 - (12 + 4) = 4 years old.\nSo, one son is 12 years old and the other is 4 years younger, making it 12 - 4 = 8 years old.\nJames wants to buy packs of 5 candles each, so he needs 8 / 5 = 1.6 packs.\nSince you can't buy a fraction of a pack, James will need to buy 2 packs of candles.\nEach pack costs $3, so James spends 2 * $3 = $<<2*3=6>>6 on candles."
