[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 start id=gsm8k_test_727
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 1/3 answer="First, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the students' cars:\n- Each student's car has 4 windows, so 64 students have \\(64 \\times 4 = 256\\) windows.\n- Hannah smashes a quarter (1/4) of these windows, so she smashes \\(256 \\times \\frac{1}{4} = 64\\) windows from the students' cars.\n\nNext, we calculate the number of windows smashed by the teachers' cars:\n- Each teacher's car has 2 windows, so 32 teachers have \\(32 \\times 2 = 64\\) windows.\n- Hannah smashes 3/4 (or 75%) of these windows, so she smashes \\(64 \\times \\frac{3}{4} = 48\\) windows from the teachers' cars.\n\nFinally, we sum up all the windows smashed:\n- Total windows smashed = windows from students' cars + windows from teachers' cars = \\(64 + 48 = 112\\).\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed 112 windows total."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 2/3 answer="First, we calculate the total number of windows smashed by the students:\nNumber of windows smashed by students = (Number of students' cars) × (Windows per car)\n= 64 × 4\n= 256\n\nNext, we calculate the total number of windows smashed by the teachers:\nNumber of windows smashed by teachers = (Number of teachers' cars) × (Windows per teacher)\n= 32 × 2\n= 64\n\nNow, we find the total number of windows smashed by both groups:\nTotal windows smashed = Number of windows smashed by students + Number of windows smashed by teachers\n= 256 + 64\n= 320\n\nFinally, we subtract the total number of windows smashed from the total cost of the parking lot to find out how much money Hannah spent on breaking windows:\nMoney spent = Total cost of parking lot - Total windows smashed\n= $100 - $320\n= -$220\n\nSince Hannah spent more than what she had, it means she didn't break any windows. Therefore, the amount of money Hannah spent is $220 less than the total cost of the parking lot."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 60/100 path 3/3 answer="First, we calculate the number of students' car windows Hannah smashed:\nNumber of students' cars = 64\nWindows per student's car = 4\nNumber of students' cars with windows = 64 * 4 = 256\n\nNext, we calculate the number of teachers' car windows Hannah smashed:\nNumber of teachers' cars = 32\nWindows per teacher's car = 2\nNumber of teachers' cars with windows = 32 * 2 = 64\n\nNow, we sum up all the windows smashed:\nTotal windows smashed = Windows from students + Windows from teachers\nTotal windows smashed = (256 * 4) + (64 * 2)\nTotal windows smashed = 1024 + 128\nTotal windows smashed = 1152\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed 1152 windows."
