mber of windows smashed by teachers = (Number of teachers' cars) × (Windows per teacher)\n= 32 × 2\n= 64\n\nNow, we find the total number of windows smashed by both groups:\nTotal windows smashed = Number of windows smashed by students + Number of windows smashed by teachers\n= 256 + 64\n= 320\n\nFinally, we subtract the total number of windows smashed from the total cost of the parking lot to find out how much money Hannah spent on breaking windows:\nMoney spent = Total cost of parking lot - Total windows smashed\n= $100 - $320\n= -$220\n\nSince Hannah spent more than what she had, it means she didn't break any windows. Therefore, the amount of money Hannah spent is $220 less than the total cost of the parking lot.": 1, "First, we calculate the number of students' car windows Hannah smashed:\nNumber of students' cars = 64\nWindows per student's car = 4\nNumber of students' cars with windows = 64 * 4 = 256\n\nNext, we calculate the number of teachers' car windows Hannah smashed:\nNumber of teachers' cars = 32\nWindows per teacher's car = 2\nNumber of teachers' cars with windows = 32 * 2 = 64\n\nNow, we sum up all the windows smashed:\nTotal windows smashed = Windows from students + Windows from teachers\nTotal windows smashed = (256 * 4) + (64 * 2)\nTotal windows smashed = 1024 + 128\nTotal windows smashed = 1152\n\nTherefore, Hannah smashed 1152 windows.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 start id=gsm8k_test_735
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 1/3 answer='To find out how many votes candidate C received, we first need to determine the number of votes each candidate received based on the percentages they obtained from the total votes (100).\n\nCandidate A got 20% of the votes:\n\\[ \\text{Votes for Candidate A} = 20\\% \\times 100 = 0.20 \\times 100 = 20 \\]\n\nCandidate B got 50% more votes than Candidate A:\n\\[ \\text{Votes for Candidate B} = 20 + (0.50 \\times 20) = 20 + 10 = 30 \\]\n\nSince the rest of the votes were given to candidate C, we can calculate the remaining votes as follows:\n\\[ \\text{Remaining Votes} = 100 - (\\text{Votes for Candidate A} + \\text{Votes for Candidate B}) = 100 - (20 + 30) = 100 - 50 = 50 \\]\n\nSo, candidate C received 50 votes.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 2/3 answer="First, calculate the number of votes candidate A received:\nCandidate A's votes = 20% of 100 = 0.2 * 100 = 20 votes\n\nNext, determine the number of votes candidate B received, which is 50% more than candidate A's votes:\nCandidate B's votes = Candidate A's votes + (50% of Candidate A's votes) = 20 + (0.5 * 20) = 20 + 10 = 30 votes\n\nNow, subtract the total votes of candidates A and B from the total number of votes to find out how many votes candidate C got:\nVotes for candidate C = Total votes - Votes for A - Votes for B = 100 - 20 - 30 = 50 votes\n\nSo, candidate C got 50 votes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 61/100 path 3/3 answer='To find out how many votes candidate C received, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the number of votes candidate A received:\n   Candidate A got 20% of the total votes, so:\n   Votes for A = 20% of 100 = 0.20 * 100 = 20\n\n2. Calculate the number of votes candidate B received:\n   Candidate B got 50% more than candidate A, so:\n   Votes for B = Votes for A + (50% of Votes for A)\n                  = 20 + (0.50 * 20)\n                  = 20 + 10\n                  = 30\n\n3. Calculate the number of votes candidate C received:\n   Total votes = Votes for A + Votes for B\n                = 20 + 30\n                = 50\n\nTherefore, candidate C received 50 votes.'
