[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 start id=gsm8k_test_775
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 1/3 answer="To determine how many wheels will be left after assembling the toys, we'll first calculate the total number of wheels needed for the cars and motorcycles separately, and then subtract these from the total number of wheels available in the box.\n\nFor the cars:\nHenry needs 57 cars, and each car requires 4 wheels. So, the total number of wheels needed for the cars is \\(57 \\times 4\\).\n\nFor the motorcycles:\nHenry needs 73 motorcycles, and each motorcycle requires 2 wheels. So, the total number of wheels needed for the motorcycles is \\(73 \\times 2\\).\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of wheels needed for both types of toys:\n\nTotal wheels needed for cars = \\(57 \\times 4 = 228\\)\nTotal wheels needed for motorcycles = \\(73 \\times 2 = 146\\)\n\nNext, we'll find out how many wheels are left in the box:\n\nWheels left in the box = Total wheels in the box - (Total wheels needed for cars + Total wheels needed for motorcycles)\n\nSubstituting the values we have:\n\nWheels left in the box = \\(650 - (228 + 146)\\)\n\nLet's do the math:\n\n\\(650 - (228 + 146) = 650 - 374 = 276\\)\n\nSo, there will be 276 wheels left in the box."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 2/3 answer='First, calculate the total number of wheels needed for the cars:\n57 cars * 4 wheels/car = 228 wheels\n\nNext, calculate the total number of wheels needed for the motorcycles:\n73 motorcycles * 2 wheels/motorcycle = 146 wheels\n\nNow, add these two amounts together to find the total number of wheels needed:\n228 wheels + 146 wheels = 374 wheels\n\nFinally, subtract the total number of wheels from the box (which contains 650 wheels) from the actual number of wheels needed:\n650 wheels - 374 wheels = 276 wheels\n\nSo, there will be 276 wheels left in the box.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 65/100 path 3/3 answer="To find out how many wheels will be left after assembling the toys, we first calculate the total number of wheels needed for the cars and motorcycles separately, and then subtract those from the total number of wheels available in the box.\n\nHenry needs:\n- 57 cars, with each car requiring 4 wheels, so 57 * 4 wheels\n- 73 motorcycles, with each motorcycle requiring 2 wheels, so 73 * 2 wheels\n\nTotal wheels needed for cars = 57 * 4 = <<57*4=228>>228 wheels\nTotal wheels needed for motorcycles = 73 * 2 = <<73*2=146>>146 wheels\n\nNow, let's add these together to get the total number of wheels needed:\n\nTotal wheels needed = Wheels for cars + Wheels for motorcycles\nTotal wheels needed = 228 + 146 = <<228+146=374>>374 wheels\n\nHenry has a box with 650 wheels in it. To find out how many wheels will be left over, we subtract the total number of wheels needed from the number of wheels in the box:\n\nWheels left = Total wheels in the box - Total wheels needed\nWheels left = 650 - 374 = <<650-374=276>>276 wheels\n\nTherefore, there will be 276 wheels left after Henry completes his toy assembly."
