[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 66/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how much it would cost to replace Mike's movie collection, we'll break down the problem into steps:\n\n1. **Calculate the number of movies in each category**:\n   - Total movies: 600\n   - Series movies: \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times 600 = 200 \\)\n   - Older movies: \\( 40\\% \\) of the remaining movies\n\n2. **Determine the number of older movies**:\n   - Older movies: \\( 0.4 \\times (600 - 200) = 0.4 \\times 400 = 160 \\)\n\n3. **Calculate the total cost of the older movies**:\n   - Cost per older movie: $5\n   - Total cost for older movies: \\( 160 \\times 5 = \\$800 \\)\n\n4. **Add up all the costs**:\n   - Normal movie cost: $10\n   - Series movies cost: $6\n   - Older movies cost: $800\n   - Total cost: \\( 10 + 6 + 800 = \\$816 \\)\n\nTherefore, the total cost to replace Mike's movie collection is $816."
