ds\nPlums: 8 pounds\nApricots: 6 pounds\n\nNow, let's calculate the cost for each type of fruit:\n\nCost of peaches: 6 pounds * $2.00/pound = $12.00\nCost of plums: 8 pounds * $1.00/pound = $8.00\nCost of apricots: 6 pounds * $3.00/pound = $18.00\n\nFinally, we'll add up all the costs to get the total amount spent:\n\nTotal cost = Cost of peaches + Cost of plums + Cost of apricots\nTotal cost = $12.00 + $8.00 + $18.00\nTotal cost = $38.00\n\nTherefore, Winston spent $38.00 on fruit.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 start id=gsm8k_test_810
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 1/3 answer='8'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out how many additional students joined by the end of May, we first need to calculate the total number of students on campus over the course of the year.\n\nStarting with 10 students:\n- January: 10 (already on campus)\n- February: 10 * 2 = 20 (doubled from Jan)\n- March: 20 * 2 = 40 (doubled from Feb)\n- April: 40 * 2 = 80 (doubled from Mar)\n- May: 80 * 2 = 160 (doubled from Apr)\n\nNow, let's sum up all these numbers:\n\n10 + 20 + 40 + 80 + 160 = 310\n\nSo, there were 310 students on campus by the end of May.\n\nIf we want to know how many additional students joined by the end of May compared to the number already on campus at the beginning of the year, we subtract the initial count from the current total:\n\n310 - 10 = 300\n\nTherefore, by the end of May, there would be 300 additional students on campus compared to when they started."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 path 3/3 answer='To determine how many additional students joined by the end of May compared to the initial number of students, we first calculate the total number of students added over the course of the year.\n\nAt the start of the year (January), there were 10 students. By the end of each month, the number of students doubles. So:\n\n- January: 10 students\n- February: 10 * 2 = 20 students\n- March: 20 * 2 = 40 students\n- April: 40 * 2 = 80 students\n- May: 80 * 2 = 160 students\n\nAdding these up gives us the total number of students added during the year:\n10 + 20 + 40 + 80 + 160 = 310 students\n\nNow, we subtract the initial number of students from the total number of students added to find out how many more students joined:\n310 - 10 = 300 students\n\nTherefore, by the end of May, 300 additional students had joined the campus, exceeding the number of students already on campus by the beginning of the year by 300.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 68/100 done id=gsm8k_test_810 prediction='8' gold='310' correct=False vote_counts={'8': 1, "To find out how many additional students joined by the end of May, we first need to calculate the total number of students on campus over the course of the year.\n\nStarting with 10 students:\n- January: 10 (already on campus)\n- February: 10 * 2 = 20 (doubled from Jan)\n- March: 20 * 2 = 40 (doubled from Feb)\n- April: 40 * 2 = 80 (doubled from Mar)\n- May: 80 * 2 = 160 (doubled from Apr)\n\nNow, let's sum up all these numbers:\n\n10 + 20 + 40 + 80 + 160 = 310\n\nSo, there were 310 students on campus by the end of May.\n\nIf we want to know how many additional students joined by the end of May compared to the number already on campus at the beginning of the year, we subtract the initial count from the current total:\n\n310 - 10 = 300\n\nTherefore, by the end of May, there would be 300 additional students on campus compared to when they started.": 1, 'To determine how many additional students joined by the end of May compared to the initial number of students, we first calculate the total number of students added over the course of the year.\n\nAt the start of the year (January), there were 10 students. By the end of each month, the number of students doubles. So:\n\n- January: 10 students\n- February: 10 * 2 = 20 students\n- March: 20 * 2 = 40 students\n- April: 40 * 2 = 80 students\n- May: 80 * 2 = 160 students\n\nAdding these up gives us the total number of students added during the year:\n10 + 20 + 40 + 80 + 160 = 310 students\n\nNow, we subtract the initial number of students from the total number of students added to find out how many more students joined:\n310 - 10 = 300 students\n\nTherefore, by the end of May, 300 additional students had joined the campus, exceeding the number of students already on campus by the beginning of the year by 300.': 1}
