[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 start id=gsm8k_test_946
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 1/3 answer="First, we calculate how many loaves of bread the bakery currently has. We know that the bakery has 40 less than seven times as many loaves as Sam had last Friday. Since Sam had 70 loaves last Friday, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Loaves of bread} = 7 \\times \\text{Sam's loaves} - 40 \\]\n\nSubstituting the given number of loaves Sam had:\n\n\\[ \\text{Loaves of bread} = 7 \\times 70 - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Loaves of bread} = 490 - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Loaves of bread} = 450 \\]\n\nTherefore, the bakery has 450 loaves of bread."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 2/3 answer="First, we calculate how many loaves of bread the bakery has based on what Sam had last Friday. Since the bakery has 40 less than seven times as many loaves of bread as Sam had last Friday, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Bakery loaves} = 7 \\times (\\text{Sam's loaves}) - 40 \\]\n\nGiven that Sam had 70 loaves last Friday, we substitute that value into the equation:\n\n\\[ \\text{Bakery loaves} = 7 \\times (70) - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Bakery loaves} = 490 - 40 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Bakery loaves} = 450 \\]\n\nSo, the bakery has 450 loaves of bread."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 77/100 path 3/3 answer='To find out how many loaves of bread the bakery has, we can set up an equation based on the information given:\n\nLet \\( S \\) represent the number of loaves of bread Sam had last Friday.\n\nAccording to the problem, the bakery has 40 less than seven times as many loaves of bread as Sam had last Friday. So we can write:\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of loaves of bread} = 7S - 40 \\]\n\nWe know that Sam had 70 loaves of bread last Friday (since \\( S = 70 \\)). Plugging this value into our equation gives us:\n\n\\[ 7(70) - 40 = 490 - 40 = 450 \\]\n\nSo, the bakery has 450 loaves of bread.'
