[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 1/3 answer="To find out how many jellyfish are in the tank, we can follow these steps:\n\n1. Calculate the number of large jellyfish:\n   - We know that a fifth of the jellyfish are large.\n   - Let \\( L \\) represent the total number of large jellyfish.\n   - So, \\( \\frac{L}{5} \\) are large.\n   \n2. Calculate the number of small jellyfish:\n   - We know that a third of the large jellyfish change color.\n   - Therefore, \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{L}{5} \\) are large that change color.\n   - This gives us \\( \\frac{L}{15} \\) small that change color.\n\n3. Add up all the jellyfish:\n   - Total number of jellyfish = Large + Small (that change color) + Blue (always blue)\n   - Total number of jellyfish = \\( \\frac{L}{5} + \\frac{L}{15} + 6 \\)\n\nLet's solve this equation step-by-step:\n\nFirst, let's combine the fractions with a common denominator:\n\\[ \\frac{L}{5} + \\frac{L}{15} = \\frac{3L}{15} + \\frac{L}{15} = \\frac{4L}{15} \\]\n\nNow, add the remaining jellyfish:\n\\[ \\frac{4L}{15} + 6 \\]\n\nWe know that when a UV light turned on, 6 jellyfish changed color, so:\n\\[ \\frac{4L}{15} + 6 = 6 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{4L}{15} = 0 \\] (since adding 6 to 6 doesn't make sense in terms of jellyfish count)\n\nSince we already have \\( \\frac{4"
