[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out how many jellyfish are in the tank, let's break down the information given:\n\n1. A fifth of the jellyfish are large.\n2. A third of the large jellyfish change color when UV light turns on.\n3. The rest of the jellyfish remain blue.\n\nFirst, calculate the number of large jellyfish:\n\\[ \\text{Number of large jellyfish} = \\frac{1}{5} \\times \\text{Total number of jellyfish} \\]\n\nNext, calculate the number of jellyfish that change color due to UV light turning on:\n\\[ \\text{Number of jellyfish changing color} = \\frac{1}{3} \\times (\\text{Number of large jellyfish}) \\]\n\nThen, subtract these numbers from the total number of jellyfish to get the number of jellyfish that remain blue:\n\\[ \\text{Remaining blue jellyfish} = \\text{Total number of jellyfish} - \\text{Number of large jellyfish} - \\text{Number of jellyfish changing color} \\]\n\nWe know that 6 jellyfish changed color, so we can set up the equation:\n\\[ 6 = \\text{Number of large jellyfish} - \\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\right) \\times (\\text{Number of large jellyfish}) \\]\n\\[ 6 = \\frac{2}{3} \\times \\text{Number of large jellyfish} \\]\n\nNow solve for the number of large jellyfish:\n\\[ \\text{Number of large jellyfish} = \\frac{6 \\times 3}{2} = 9 \\]\n\nSince there were 9 large jellyfish initially, we can now find the number of blue jellyfish:\n\\[ \\text{Number of blue jellyfish} = \\text{Total number of jellyfish} - \\text{Number of large jellyfish} -"
