\\[ \\text{Number of blue jellyfish} = \\text{Total number of jellyfish} - \\text{Number of large jellyfish} -": 1, "To solve this problem, we can break down the information given:\n\n1. We know there are multiple jellyfish in the tank.\n2. A fifth (or \\( \\frac{1}{5} \\)) of these jellyfish are large.\n3. Among the large jellyfish, a third (or \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\)) change their color when UV light turns on.\n\nGiven that 6 jellyfish changed color when UV light was turned on, let's denote the total number of jellyfish as \\( J \\).\n\nFrom the information:\n- A fifth of the jellyfish are large, so \\( \\frac{J}{5} \\) are large.\n- Among the large jellyfish, \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\) change color, so \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{J}{5} = 6 \\).\n\nNow, let's solve for \\( J \\):\n\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{J}{5} = 6 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{J}{15} = 6 \\]\n\\[ J = 6 \\times 15 \\]\n\\[ J = 90 \\]\n\nSo, there are 90 jellyfish in the tank.": 1}
