[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's calculate the number of scoops Gomer ate:\n\nGomer ate 5 less than 23 scoops, so he ate:\n23 - 5 = 18 scoops of mashed potatoes.\n\nNext, we'll determine how many potatoes it took to make those 18 scoops:\n\nIt takes 3 less than 6 scoops to make 1 scoop of mashed potatoes. So, for 18 scoops, it would take:\n(18 / 6) * 3 = 3 * 3 = 9 potatoes.\n\nTherefore, Gomer ate 9 potatoes."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 85/100 path 3/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many scoops of mashed potatoes Gomer ate. Since he ate 5 less than 23 scoops, we subtract 5 from 23:\n\n23 - 5 = 18 scoops\n\nNext, we need to determine how many potatoes it takes to make 1 less than 3 scoops. We know that it takes 3 less than 6 potatoes to make 1 scoop, so we multiply 6 by 3:\n\n6 * 3 = 18 potatoes\n\nNow we can find out how many potatoes Gomer ate by adding the number of scoops to the number of potatoes needed for each type of potato:\n\n18 (scoops) + 18 (potatoes) = 36 potatoes\n\nSo, Gomer ate 36 potatoes."
