[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1182
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's determine how many books Bob can buy with his total budget. With $27000, he can buy 100 books at $500 each, so:\n\nTotal cost for 100 books = $27000 / 500 = $54\n\nNow, we know that he spent $27000 on books but only has $54 left over. This means he has enough money to buy all 100 books.\n\nTo find out how many books he can buy per school, we divide the remaining budget by the number of schools:\n\nBooks per school = Remaining budget / Number of schools\nBooks per school = $54 / 3 schools\nBooks per school = $18\n\nSo, Bob can buy 18 books per school."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 2/3 answer='To determine how many books each school can buy, we first need to find out how much money Bob has left after buying 100 books with $500. This can be calculated as follows:\n\n\\[ \\text{Money left} = \\$27000 - \\$500 = \\$26500 \\]\n\nNext, we divide the remaining money by the number of schools to see how many books each school can buy:\n\n\\[ \\text{Books per school} = \\frac{\\$26500}{3} \\approx \\$8833.33 \\]\n\nSince the question asks specifically about how many books each school can buy, and assuming the question intends for us to round down (as it implies whole books), the answer would be:\n\n\\[ \\text{Books per school} = 8833 \\]'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 88/100 path 3/3 answer='First, we calculate how many books Bob can buy with his total budget of $27000 if each book costs $500. This gives us:\n\n$27000 / $500 = 54 books\n\nNow, since Bob wants to distribute these 54 books among 3 schools, we divide the number of books by the number of schools to find out how many books each school can get:\n\n54 books / 3 schools = 18 books per school\n\nTherefore, Bob can buy 18 books per school.'
