[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 95/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1287 prediction='23' gold='84' correct=False vote_counts={'23': 1, "First, let's identify the ages of the siblings:\n- The older brother is 12 years old.\n- The younger brother is also 12 years old (since they are the same age).\n- There are 3 sisters, each 16 years old.\n\nNow, let's calculate the total age of all the siblings:\n- The older brother + Younger brother + 3 sisters = 12 + 12 + 3 * 16 = 12 + 12 + 48 = 72 years.\n\nSo, the total age of all these siblings is 72 years.": 1, "First, let's determine the ages of the brothers and sisters:\n\n- The older brother is 12 years old.\n- Since one brother is half the age of the older brother, the younger brother is 12 * 2 = 24 years old.\n\nNow we have:\n- 2 brothers (each 12 years old)\n- 3 sisters (all the same age, 16 years old)\n\nNext, we calculate the total age of all the siblings:\n\n- Total age of the brothers: 2 * 12 = 24 years\n- Total age of the sisters: 3 * 16 = 48 years\n\nAdding these together gives us the total age of all the siblings: 24 + 48 = 72 years.\n\nTherefore, the total age of all these siblings is 72 years.": 1}
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1300
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 1/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 1/3 answer="To calculate Josh's earnings for two weeks, we first need to determine his weekly earnings:\n\n1. **Daily Service Hours:** \n   - Josh services 3 cars each day.\n   - There are 7 days in a workweek (Monday through Friday).\n   - Therefore, he works 3 cars/day × 7 days/week = 21 cars/week.\n\n2. **Weekly Earnings Calculation:**\n   - He earns $4 per car.\n   - So, his weekly earnings would be 21 cars/week × $4/car = $<<21*4=84>>84.\n\n3. **Two Weeks' Earnings Calculation:**\n   - Since there are 2 weeks in total (including holidays), his earnings over two weeks would be 2 weeks × $84/week = $<<2*84=168>>168.\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $168 in two weeks."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 2/3 answer='First, calculate how many days Josh works in a week:\n- Monday through Friday: 5 days\n- Saturday: 1 day\n- Sunday: 1 day\n- Wednesday: 1 day\n\nSo, total working days in a week = 5 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 8 days\n\nNow, calculate his earnings from servicing cars:\n- Earnings per service = $4\n- Number of services per day = 3\n\nTotal earnings per day = 3 * $4 = $12/day\n\nEarnings over 8 days = 8 * $12 = $96\n\nJosh makes $96 per week (since there are 52 weeks in a year).\n\nTo find out how much he makes in 2 weeks:\n- Total earnings in 2 weeks = $96/day * 2 days/week = $192/week\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $192 in 2 weeks.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 96/100 path 3/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many days Josh works in a week:\n- There are 5 working days (Monday through Friday) and 2 days off (Sunday and Wednesday), so 5 + 2 = 7 days in a week.\n\nNext, we'll calculate how many cars he services in a week:\n- He services 3 cars each day, so 3 cars/day * 7 days/week = 21 cars/week.\n\nNow, we can calculate his total earnings:\n- He gets paid $4 per car, so 21 cars/week * $4/car = $<<21*4=84>>84/week.\n\nFinally, we'll calculate his weekly earnings:\n- He works 7 days/week, so $84/week * 7 days/week = $<<84*7=588>>588/week.\n\nTo find out how much he makes in 2 weeks, we multiply his weekly earnings by 2:\n- $588/week * 2 weeks = $<<588*2=1176>>1176.\n\nTherefore, Josh makes $1176 in 2 weeks."
