[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 97/100 path 1/3 answer="First, let's calculate how many cookies Randy had initially:\n\nOatmeal cookies: 9\nChocolate chip cookies: 4\nSugar cookies: 5\n\nTotal initial cookies: 9 + 4 + 5 = 18\n\nRandy ate:\n- 3 oatmeal cookies (for the early snack)\n- 1 chocolate chip cookie (lunch)\n- 2 sugar cookies (for lunch)\n\nTotal eaten cookies: 3 + 1 + 2 = 6\n\nNow, let's subtract the eaten cookies from the total:\n\nRemaining cookies: 18 - 6 = 12\n\nThen, we'll account for the cookies Randy baked for dinner:\n\nBaked oatmeal cookies: 4\nBaked chocolate chip cookies: 4\nBaked sugar cookies: 4\n\nTotal baked cookies: 4 + 4 + 4 = 12\n\nFinally, we'll sum up all the remaining cookies:\n\nTotal cookies now: 12 (remaining) + 12 (baked) = 24\n\nSo, Randy now has 24 cookies."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 97/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 97/100 path 2/3 answer="To find out how many cookies Randy has left, we'll start with the initial number of each type of cookie and subtract the ones he ate or gave away.\n\nInitially:\n- Oatmeal cookies: 9\n- Chocolate chip cookies: 4\n- Sugar cookies: 5\n\nAfter eating:\n- Oatmeal cookies: 9 - 3 = 6\n- Chocolate chip cookies: 4 - 2 = 2\n- Sugar cookies: 5 - 2 = 3\n\nThen baking:\n- Oatmeal cookies: 4 (baked) + 4 (from dinner) = 8\n- Chocolate chip cookies: 2 (baked) + 2 (from dinner) = 4\n- Sugar cookies: 3 (baked) + 3 (from dinner)\n\nNow, let's calculate the total number of cookies:\n\n- Total cookies: 8 (oatmeal) + 4 (chocolate chip) + 3 (sugar) = 15\n\nSo, Randy has 15 cookies now."
