[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 1/3 answer="To determine how long it took Vanessa to complete her part of the race, we'll first find out how far Aaron ran and then figure out how long it took Vanessa to cover that distance.\n\nFrom the information given:\n- Vanessa ran 4 miles.\n- Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, so he runs \\(2 \\times 4 = 8\\) miles per hour.\n- Vanessa runs at a speed of \\(16 \\text{ minutes} / 4 \\text{ miles} = 4 \\text{ minutes per mile}\\).\n\nNow, let's calculate how long it takes Vanessa to run 8 miles:\n\\[ \\text{Time taken by Vanessa} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}}{\\text{Speed}} = \\frac{8 \\text{ miles}}{4 \\text{ miles/hour}} = 2 \\text{ hours}. \\]\n\nSince there are 60 minutes in an hour, we convert 2 hours into minutes:\n\\[ \\text{Time taken by Vanessa} = 2 \\text{ hours} \\times 60 \\text{ minutes/hour} = 120 \\text{ minutes}. \\]\n\nTherefore, Vanessa took 120 minutes to complete her part of the race."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 2/3 answer="First, let's determine how far Aaron ran. Since he runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, and Vanessa ran 4 miles, Aaron would have run \\(4 \\times 2 = 8\\) miles. \n\nNow, we know that Aaron took 16 minutes to complete his part of the race. To find out how long it takes Vanessa to complete her part, we divide the time Aaron took by the number of miles he ran:\n\n\\[ \\text{Time for Vanessa} = \\frac{\\text{Time taken by Aaron}}{\\text{Distance Aaron ran}} = \\frac{16}{8} = 2 \\text{ minutes} \\]\n\nTherefore, Vanessa took 2 minutes to complete her part of the race."
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 3/3 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 99/100 path 3/3 answer='To find out how long it took Vanessa to complete her part of the race, we first need to determine how far Aaron ran. Since Aaron runs each mile twice as fast as Vanessa, and Vanessa runs 4 miles, Aaron would have run:\n\n\\[ 4 \\text{ miles} \\times 2 = 8 \\text{ miles} \\]\n\nNow, we know that Aaron completed his part of the race in 16 minutes. To find out how long it took Vanessa to complete her part, we divide the time it took Aaron by 2 (since he ran at twice the speed):\n\n\\[ \\frac{16 \\text{ minutes}}{2} = 8 \\text{ minutes} \\]\n\nSo, Vanessa took 8 minutes to complete her part of the race.'
